}}\n{{USSecHUD}}\n{{Kennedy family}}\n{{Clinton cabinet}}\n{{Current New York statewide political officials}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo|*]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Albany Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:American gun control activists]]\n[[Category:American lawyers and judges of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Archbishop Molloy High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Clinton administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Cuomo family]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Kennedy family]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of New York politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York State Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:People from Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:2008 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Housing and Urban Development]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|56th Governor of New York}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Andrew Cuomo\n| image        = Andrew Cuomo by Pat Arnow cropped.jpeg\n| order        = 56th\n| office       = Governor of New York\n| lieutenant   = [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]]<br>[[Kathy Hochul]]\n| term_start   = January 1, 2011\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = [[David Paterson]]\n| successor    =\n| order2       = 64th\n| office2      = Attorney General of New York\n| governor2    = [[Eliot Spitzer]] <br> [[David Paterson]]\n| term_start2  = January 1, 2007\n| term_end2    = December 31, 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[Eliot Spitzer]]\n| successor2   = [[Eric Schneiderman]]\n| office3      = 11th [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]]\n| president3   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| term_start3  = January 29, 1997\n| term_end3    = January 20, 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Henry Cisneros]]\n| successor3   = [[Mel Mart\u00ednez]]\n| office4      = [[Department of Housing and Urban Development|Assistant Secretary of Housing and Urban Development for Community Planning and Development]]\n| president4   = Bill Clinton\n| term_start4  = May 28, 1993\n| term_end4    = January 29, 1997\n| predecessor4 = Skirma Kondratas\n| successor4   = [[Saul N. Ramirez Jr.|Saul Ramirez, Jr.]]\n| birth_name   = Andrew Mark Cuomo\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1957|12|6}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Kerry Kennedy]]|1990|2005|end=div}}\n| partner      = [[Sandra Lee (chef)|Sandra Lee]] (2005\u20132019)\n| children     = 3\n| parents      = [[Mario Cuomo]] <br> [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda Raffa]]\n| relatives    = [[Chris Cuomo]] (brother) <br> [[Margaret Cuomo]] (sister)\n| residence    = [[New York State Executive Mansion|Executive Mansion]]\n| education    = [[Fordham University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) <br> [[Albany Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website      = {{url|governor.ny.gov|Government website}}\n| signature=Andrew_Cuomo_Signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Mark Cuomo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}; born December 6, 1957) is an American politician, author, and lawyer serving since 2011 as the [[List of Governors of New York|56th]] [[governor of New York]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was elected to the same position his father, [[Mario Cuomo]], held for three terms.\n\nBorn in [[New York City]], Cuomo is a graduate of [[Fordham University]] and [[Albany Law School]] of [[Union University (New York)|Union University, New York]]. He began his career working as the campaign manager for his father, then as an assistant district attorney in New York City before entering private law practice. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP USA) and was appointed chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, a position he held from 1990 to 1993.\n\nIn 1993, Cuomo joined the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton Administration]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]]. From 1997 to 2001, he served as the [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]].\n\nIn [[2006 New York Attorney General election|2006]], Cuomo was elected [[New York State Attorney General|Attorney General of New York]]. He won the election as [[Governor of New York]] in [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] and has been reelected twice after winning primaries against liberal challengers [[Zephyr Teachout]] ([[2014 New York gubernatorial election|2014]]) and [[Cynthia Nixon]] ([[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]]). During his governorship, Cuomo oversaw the passage of a law legalizing [[Same-sex marriage in New York|same-sex marriage]] in New York; creation of the United States Climate Alliance, a group of states committed to fighting [[climate change]] by following the terms of the Paris Climate Accords; passage of the strictest [[NY SAFE Act|gun control]] law in the U.S.; [[Affordable Care Act|Medicaid expansion]]; a new tax code that raised taxes for the wealthy and lowered taxes for the middle class; paid family leave; an increase in the minimum wage; wage equality; and legislation legalizing medical marijuana.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCuomo was born in the [[Queens]] borough of [[New York City]],<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/andrew-cuomo-21024931 | title=Andrew Cuomo Biography: Government Official, Lawyer (1957\u2013)| publisher= [[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV channel)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | accessdate= May 25, 2015}}</ref> the elder son of five children born to lawyer and later governor of New York, [[Mario Cuomo]] and [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda]] (''n\u00e9e'' Raffa).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\">{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Blauner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--cCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|title=All Star Family Feud: The Governor's In-Laws Battle Over a Father's Legacy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=February 13, 1989|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref> His parents were both of [[Italian-American|Italian]] descent; his paternal grandparents were from [[Nocera Inferiore]] and [[Tramonti, Campania|Tramonti]] in the [[Campania]] region of southern Italy, while his maternal grandparents were from [[Sicily]] (his grandfather from [[Messina]]).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\" /><ref name=Newsday10201988>{{cite news| first =Michael| last =Arena | author2 =Marianne Arneberg |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/104068528.html?dids=104068528:104068528&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+20%2C+1988&author=By+Michael+Arena+and+Marianne+Arneberg&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=Cuomo's+Father-in-Law+Dies&pqatl=google|title=Cuomo's Father-in-Law Dies|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 20, 1988|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> His younger brother, [[Chris Cuomo]], is a [[CNN]] journalist. His elder sister is noted radiologist [[Margaret Cuomo]].<ref name=\"NYTimes112310\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Barbaro|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html|title=All That Time Serving the Public? Very Sexy|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=December 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101125130807/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html| archivedate= November 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from St. Gerard Majella's School in 1971<ref>Campanile, Carl. \"[https://nypost.com/2015/05/13/cuomo-and-cardinal-dolan-tout-parochial-school-tax-break/ Cuomo and Cardinal Dolan tout parochial school tax break],\" ''New York Post'', May 13, 2015.</ref> and [[Archbishop Molloy High School]] in 1975.<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Fordham University]] in 1979, and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Albany Law School]] in 1982.<ref name=\"biography.com\"/>\n\n== Early career ==\nDuring his father's [[New York gubernatorial election, 1982|1982 campaign for Governor]], Cuomo was campaign manager, and then joined the governor's staff as one of his father's policy advisors and sometime Albany roommate,<ref name=NYm>Smith, Chris. \"[https://nymag.com/news/features/andrew-cuomo-2013-4/ The Albany Machiavelli],\" New York, April 14, 2013.</ref> earning $1 a year.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\">{{cite news |first=Patrice|last=O'Shaughnessy|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/09/27/2009-09-27_andrew_cuomo_from_horror_on_the_hudson_to_democrats_chosen_son.html |title=Andrew Cuomo: From Horror on the Hudson to Democrats' chosen son|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |date=September 27, 2009|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1984 to 1985, Cuomo was a New York assistant district attorney and briefly worked at the law firm of Blutrich, Falcone & Miller. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP) in 1986 and left his law firm to run HELP full-time in 1988.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\" /> From 1990 to 1993, during the administration of [[Mayor of New York City|New York City mayor]], [[David Dinkins]], Cuomo was chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, which was charged with developing policies to address the homeless issue in the city and developing more housing options.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Secretary of HUD ==\n[[File:HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Cuomo as HUD Secretary]]\nAndrew Cuomo was appointed to the [[Department of Housing and Urban Development]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in 1993, a member of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s administration.<ref name=\"HUD\" /> After the departure of Secretary [[Henry Cisneros]] at the end of Clinton's first term under the cloud of an FBI investigation,<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite news | last =Evans | first =Judith | title =HUD's Cisneros to Leave a Legacy of Public Housing Reform | work =[[The Washington Post]] | page =E01 | date =November 30, 1996 | url =https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/cisneros/stories/cis113096.htm | accessdate =January 12, 2011 }}</ref> Cuomo was unanimously confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] to succeed him as [[Secretary of HUD]]. Cuomo served as Secretary from January 1997 until the Clinton administration ended in 2001.<ref name=\"HUD\" />\n\nIn 2000, Cuomo led HUD efforts to negotiate an agreement with the United States' largest handgun manufacturer, [[Smith & Wesson]], that required Smith & Wesson to change the design, distribution, and marketing of guns to make them safer and to help keep them out of the hands of children and criminals.<ref name=\"HUD\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm |title=Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Archives, U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development |accessdate=May 20, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527090837/http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm| archivedate= May 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Budgets enacted during his term contained initiatives to increase the supply of affordable housing and homeownership, and to create jobs and economic development. These included new rental assistance subsidies, reforms to integrate public housing, higher limits on mortgages insured by the [[Federal Housing Administration]], a crackdown on housing discrimination, expanded programs to help homeless people get housing and jobs, and creation of new [[Empowerment Zone|empowerment zone]]s.\n\n[[File:CuomoSummers.jpg|thumb|upright|Cuomo as HUD Secretary holding a press conference with then Treasury Secretary [[Larry Summers]]]]\nDuring Cuomo's tenure as HUD Secretary, he called for an increase in home ownership.<ref name=\"Fairbanks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece |title=Cuomo's HUD career under scrutiny |work=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 21, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010|first=Phil|last=Fairbanks| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100825154017/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece| archivedate= August 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> He also pushed government-sponsored lenders [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]] to buy more home loans issued to poor homeowners, in an attempt to end discrimination against minorities.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |title=As HUD Chief, Cuomo Earns a Mixed Score |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 23, 2010 |author1=David M. Halbfinger |author2=Michael Powell |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127034455/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |archivedate=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some believe that this helped lead to the 2007-2010 [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /><ref name=\"Barrett\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |title=Andrew Cuomo and Fannie and Freddie |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=August 5, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |first=Wayne |last=Barrett |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722145449/http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |archivedate=July 22, 2010 }}</ref> Edward J. Pinto, former chief credit officer at Fannie Mae, said \"they should have known the risks were large. Cuomo was pushing mortgage bankers to make loans and basically saying you have to offer a loan to everybody.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /> But others disagree with the assessment that Cuomo caused the crisis. [[Dean Baker]], co-director of the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]], said Cuomo \"was a contributor in terms of him being a cheerleader, but I don't think we can pin too much blame on him.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" />\n\nAccording to libertarian author and critic [[James Bovard]], Cuomo was obsessed with changing HUD's image, as Cuomo declared, \"The PR is the important thing I do ... Eighty percent of the battle is communications.\" He championed a new program called Community Builders, created without appropriation by Congress, for 800 new HUD employees with computers to be paid as much as $100,000. In a June 16, 1999, speech, Cuomo declared that one purpose of the program was to fight against HUD's abolition. In August 1999, Community Builders distributed a letter to community groups to fight against proposed tax cuts. One HUD official declared that Community Builders were seen as \"Democratic [[ward heeler]]s who act as a pipeline between Democratic city officials, party leaders, and the administration and the [[Democratic National Committee]].\"\n\nIn 1998, Clinton-appointed HUD inspector general Susan Gaffney testified to a Senate committee that she was the victim of \"'escalating' attacks on her office by Cuomo and 'his key aides,' including cooked-up charges of racism, insubordination, malfeasance, and general dirty-dealing.\" In 1999, Gaffney's office concluded that \"most (15 out of 19) Community Builders' goals were activities rather than actual accomplishments.\" and that Cuomo's initiatives \"had a crippling effect on many of HUD's ongoing operations.\"<ref>{{cite book | first=James | last=Bovard | authorlink=James Bovard | year= 2000 | title= Feeling Your Pain: The Explosion and Abuse Of Government Power in the Clinton-Gore Years | publisher= St. Martin's Press | location= New York | id=0-312-23082-6 | pages= 182\u2013184}}</ref>  Gaffney retired in May 2001, shortly after the department reached a $490,000 settlement with a black employee who had accused her of racial discrimination in passing him over for a promotion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nakashima |first=Ellen |agency=''[[Washington Post]]'' |date=May 6, 2001 |title=HUD's Inspector General Retiring After Racial-Bias Suit Settlement |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-2001-05-06-0105060155-story.html |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |location=Deerfield Beach, FL}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Cuomo's tenure, HUD was routinely included on the General Accounting Office's biannual watch list of government programs whose poor management made them prone to fraud.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite news |last=Mahler |first=Jonathan |date=August 11, 2010 |title=The Making of Andrew Cuomo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/15/magazine/15Cuomo-t.html |work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |page=30}}</ref> During his time in office, two of HUD's four main departments were removed from the GAO list.<ref name=\"Making\"/> In addition, the department cut 15 percent of its staff as part of a Cuomo initiative to streamline its operations.<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n== 2002 New York gubernatorial election ==\n{{see also|2002 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo first ran for the Democratic nomination for Governor of New York in 2002. He was initially the favorite for nomination and led in fund-raising and polls, but his campaign took serious damage after a [[gaffe]] when Cuomo said (in reference to the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks]]) \"[[George Pataki|Pataki]] stood behind the leader. He held the leader's coat. He was a great assistant to the leader. But he was not a leader. Cream rises to the top, and [[Rudy Giuliani]] rose to the top.\" His remarks were widely derided; even his father, former governor [[Mario Cuomo]], later admitted it was a blunder.<ref name=\"Dreher\">{{cite news|first=Rod|last=Dreher |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|title=Where the Son Doesn't Follow|work=[[National Review]]|date=September 4, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020910104631/http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|archivedate=September 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the state convention, Cuomo withdrew from consideration after concluding that he had little chance of support as opposed to the favored party candidate, [[New York State Comptroller|State Comptroller]] [[Carl McCall]].<ref name=\"Schneider\">{{cite news| first=Bill| last=Schneider| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|title=Let a political connection be your umbrella?|work=Inside Politics|publisher=CNN|date=September 6, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050319094326/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|archivedate=March 19, 2005}}</ref> McCall went on to lose the general election to [[George Pataki]].\n\n== New York attorney general ==\n=== Election ===\n{{main|2006 New York Attorney General election}}\nCuomo declared his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[New York State Attorney General|New York State attorney general]] in 2006, and on May 30, 2006, captured the Democratic Party's endorsement, receiving 65% of the delegates. Though Cuomo won the endorsement, former [[New York City Public Advocate|New York City public advocate]] [[Mark J. Green]] and two-time candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of New York|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Charlie King (politician)|Charlie King]], also earned places on the Democratic [[primary election|ballot]].<ref name=\"Hicks\">{{cite news|first=Jonathan P.|last=Hicks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/31/nyregion/31ag.html|title=Cuomo Wins Democrats' Backing in Primary Race for Attorney General|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 31, 2006|accessdate=July 23, 2007}}</ref> King dropped out of the race before the primary and endorsed Cuomo.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews022610\">{{cite news|first=Elizabeth|last=Benjamin|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|title=Sharpton Praises Paterson, Won't Endorse Cuomo Today | location=New York |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=February 26, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303002407/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|archivedate=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCuomo won the primary with a majority of the vote, defeating his nearest opponent by over 20%. Clinching the Democratic party nomination was considered a significant rebound following his unsuccessful and unpopular 2002 gubernatorial campaign and at the nominating convention, June O'Neill, the Democratic chairwoman of [[St. Lawrence County]], called him \"New York's own Comeback Kid.\"<ref name=\"Hicks\" /> He won the [[general election]] against the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee, former [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[District attorney]] [[Jeanine Pirro]] on November 7, 2006, winning 58% of the vote.\n\n=== Tenure ===\n==== Police surveillance, 2007 ====\n{{main|Eliot Spitzer political surveillance controversy}}\nOn July 23, 2007, Cuomo's office admonished the [[Eliot Spitzer|Spitzer administration]] for ordering the State Police to keep special records of then-Senate majority leader [[Joseph Bruno]]'s whereabouts when he traveled with police escorts in New York City.<ref name=\"nyt072307\">{{cite news|first=Danny|last=Hakim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/23/nyregion/23cnd-spitzer.html|title=Spitzer's Staff Misused Police, Report Finds|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 23, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2007}}</ref> At the discretion of top officials of the Spitzer administration, the [[New York State Police]] created documents meant to cause political damage to Bruno.<ref name=\"ijour072307\">{{cite news|first=Cara |last=Matthews |url=http://www.theithacajournal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070723/NEWS01/70723006/1002 |title=Cuomo: Spitzer aides used state police to try to damage Bruno |work=[[The Ithaca Journal]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://m.lohud.com/detail.jsp?key=62289&full=1 |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> Spitzer responded by accepting responsibility and issuing an apology to Bruno.<ref name=\"nyt072307\" /><ref name=\"siadv\">{{cite news |first=Sally |last=Goldenberg |url=http://blog.silive.com/advanceupdate/2007/07/report_governor_office_compil.html|title=Report: Governor's office compiled, leaked data on Bruno |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007}}{{dead link|date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Student loan inquiry, 2007 ====\nIn 2007, Cuomo was active in a high-profile investigation into lending practices and anti-competitive relationships between student lenders and universities. Specifically, many universities steered student borrowers to a \"preferred lender,\" which resulted in the borrowers' incurring higher interest rates. This led to changes in lending policy at many major American universities. Many universities also rebated millions of dollars in fees back to affected borrowers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/banking/2007-04-10-cuomo-student-loan-probe_N.htm |title=Cuomo: School loan corruption widespread|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=April 8, 2008| date=April 10, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Doug|last=Lederman|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/05/15/texas|title=The First Casualty|publisher=Inside Higher Education|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=April 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CuomoAckerman.jpg|thumb|240px|Cuomo with Representative [[Gary Ackerman]]]]\n\n==== Usenet, 2008 ====\nOn June 10, 2008, Cuomo announced that three major Internet service providers ([[Verizon Communications]], [[Time Warner Cable]], and [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]]) would \"shut down major sources of online [[child pornography]]\" by no longer hosting many [[Usenet]] groups. Time Warner Cable ceased offering Usenet altogether, Sprint ended access to the 18,408 newsgroups in the [[alt.* hierarchy]], and Verizon limited its Usenet offerings to the approximately 3,000 [[Big 8 (Usenet)|Big 8]] newsgroups. The move came after Cuomo's office located 88 different newsgroups to which child pornography had been posted.<ref>Rosencrance, Lisa. \"[http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9095778 3 top ISPs to block access to sources of child porn].\" ''[[Computer World]]''. June 8, 2008. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"DeJeanNotDeadYet2\">DeJean, David. \"Usenet: Not Dead Yet.\" ''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]''. Tuesday October 7, 2008. [https://www.pcworld.com/article/151989-2/usenet_not_dead_yet.html 2]. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=McCullagh | first= Declan | title= N.Y. attorney general forces ISPs to curb Usenet access | url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-9964895-38.html | date= June 10, 2008 | publisher=CNET News | accessdate=April 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==== 2008 Obama remarks ====\nIn 2008, Cuomo said of the Democratic Party candidate [[Barack Obama]], who was running against [[Hillary Clinton]], the candidate Cuomo supported: \"You can't shuck and jive at a press conference.\" Cuomo received criticism from some for his use of the phrase. [[Roland S. Martin|Roland Martin]] of [[CNN]] said that \"'[[shuckin' and jivin']]' have long been words used as a negative assessment of African Americans, along the lines of a 'foot-shufflin' [[Negro]].'\"<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/01/11/martin-shucking-and-jiving-and-the-campaign-trail/ \"Martin: 'Shucking and jiving' and the campaign trail\"], CNN Political Ticker \u2013 CNN.com Blogs, January 11, 2008.</ref>\n\n==== Corruption and fraud investigations, 2009 ====\nCuomo investigated a corruption scandal, \"fraudulent scheme to extract kickbacks\", which involved New York investigators, the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]], and [[state attorney general|attorneys general]] in dozens of states.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/business/15leuschen.html Go-Between Tied Funds to Carlyle]. New York Times, May 14, 2009</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, Cuomo launched a suit against the [[United Homeless Organization]], a New York charity. He charged that the majority of the group's income was not used to provide services to the homeless, but was diverted to the founders for unrelated personal expenses.<ref name=\"nyp_20091123\">{{citation | title=Homeless beggar jars a sham: AG | publisher=[[New York Post]] | date=2009-11-24 | url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/suit_put_cork_in_it_jugheads_GvF3qaHCib8Xh5AY86i68O?offset=16#comments#ixzz0Xmpl4OA1 | accessdate=2009-11-24 | first1=Melissa | last1=Klein | first2=Kevin | last2=Fasick | first3=Chuck | last3=Bennett}}</ref> In 2010, Judge [[Barbara R. Kapnick]] granted the judgement and forced the group to disband.<ref name=\"UHO Shut Down\">{{cite news| url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/judge_rules_hucksters_permanently_ahPPxEVrVEHlimCcLjlQ4I| title=Judge rules to permanently shut down faux homeless charity, but hucksters still out in force|last=Bennett|first=Chuck|date=|work=New York Post|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Potential U.S. Senate appointment ==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in New York, 2010#Potential candidates|l1=Possible appointment choices for the New York Senate seat}}\nAfter [[Hillary Clinton]] became President Obama's choice for [[U.S. Secretary of State|U.S. secretary of state]], then-New York governor [[David Paterson]] was charged with appointing a temporary replacement until a [[United States Senate special election in New York, 2010|special election]]. Cuomo was seen as a leading contender for this appointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/22/us/politics/22hillary.html|title=If Clinton Should Win, Who Would Take Her Place?|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=January 22, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Chan, Sewell |author2= Richard P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref><ref name=WaHfCS /> [[Caroline Kennedy]] (also the first cousin of Cuomo's ex-wife) was another leading contender, but withdrew for personal reasons two days before Paterson was set to announce his choice, leaving Cuomo and U.S. representative [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] as the most likely appointees.<ref name=WaHfCS>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/04/us/politics/04senateseat.html|title=Wishing and Hoping for Clinton's Seat|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=October 4, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html|title=New York Weighs Options to Fill the Seat of Senator Clinton |accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=November 21, 2008|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081210011131/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html| archivedate= December 10, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On January 23, Paterson announced he would appoint Gillibrand to the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/23/gillibrand.profile/index.html | title=N.Y. governor names Clinton successor | author=Silverleib, Alan |publisher=CNN | date=January 23, 2009 | accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Governor of New York ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2010 ====\n{{main|2010 New York gubernatorial election}}\nOn September 18, 2009, advisors to President Barack Obama informed Governor [[David Paterson]] that the president believed he should withdraw his 2010 gubernatorial candidacy, stepping aside for \"popular Attorney General Andrew Cuomo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/region-state/obama-cordial-but-cool-to-gov-paterson-1.1465587 |title=Obama cordial but cool to Gov. David Paterson |work=Newsday |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2010}}</ref> On January 23, 2010, the New York ''Daily News'' reported that Cuomo would announce plans for a gubernatorial campaign at the end of March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| title=Source says Andrew Cuomo will announce plans to run for New York Governor in March|date=January 23, 2010|accessdate=January 24, 2010|author=Molloy, Joanna|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]| location=New York | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100127181447/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| archivedate= January 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Later reports indicated Cuomo would announce his gubernatorial campaign coinciding with the state Democratic Convention in late May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ao6UppVoMprA |title=Cuomo Said to Wait for N.Y. Convention to Declare Governor Run |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 30, 2005 |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |first=Henry |last=Goldman}}</ref> On May 22, 2010, Cuomo announced his run for governor in a video posted to his campaign website. Cuomo announced his choice for lieutenant governor on May 26, 2010: Mayor of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]].<ref name=\"DuffySelection\">{{cite news|url=http://rochester.ynn.com/content/top_stories/505988/cuomo-names-mayor-duffy-as-running-mate/|title=Cuomo Names Mayor Duffy as Running Mate|work=Your News Now (YNN) Rochester|date=May 26, 2010|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 2, 2010, general election, Cuomo faced Republican [[Carl Paladino]], a [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]-based businessman who had been heavily supported by the [[Tea Party movement]]. Cuomo won the election for governor by a landslide, winning 62.6% of the vote. Paladino performed strongly in his native Buffalo area, while Cuomo performed well in the eastern part of the state as well as downstate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208193115/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|url-status=dead|title=\"Long Islanders put Paladino to test as their cup of tea,\" ''Buffalo News'', September 12, 2010.|archivedate=February 8, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:NYGov10County.png|thumb|Election results by county]]\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | New York gubernatorial general election results, 2010 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |title=NYS Board of Elections Governor/Lt. Governor Election Returns November 2, 2010 |accessdate=2013-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105210422/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Candidate\n! st