d-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| [[Carl Paladino]]\n| Greg Edwards\n| align=\"right\" | 1,547,857\n| align=\"right\" | 33.53%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 6.41%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#0BDA51; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n| [[Howie Hawkins]]\n| Gloria Mattera\n| align=\"right\" | 59,906\n| align=\"right\" | 1.30%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.41%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Warren Redlich]]\n| Alden Link\n| align=\"right\" | 48,359\n| align=\"right\" | 1.05%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.74%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#703642; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Rent Is Too Damn High Party|Rent Is Too Damn High]]\n| [[Jimmy McMillan]]\n| None\n| align=\"right\" | 41,129\n| align=\"right\" | 0.89%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.61%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#C9FFE5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Freedom Party of New York (2010)|Freedom]]\n| [[Charles Barron]]\n| Eva M. Doyle\n| align=\"right\" | 24,571\n| align=\"right\" | 0.53%\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B5A642; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Anti-Prohibition\n| [[Kristin M. Davis]]\n| Tanya Gendelman\n| align=\"right\" | 20,421\n| align=\"right\" | 0.44%\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | '' Scattering''\n| align=\"right\" | 4,836\n| align=\"right\" | 0.10%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\"| '''Majority'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,363,019'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''29.52%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 9.06%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''4,616,836'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.00%'''\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| colspan=\"6\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Hold'''\n|}\n\nIn addition to the parties fielding candidates, New York's [[electoral fusion]] laws allow parties to cross-endorse candidates. The [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]] and [[Working Families Party of New York|Working Families Party]] cross-endorsed Andrew Cuomo, while the [[Conservative Party of New York|Conservative Party]] and [[Taxpayers Party of New York|Taxpayers Party]] cross-endorsed Carl Paladino. The Independence Party line received 146,648 votes (5.0% of Cuomo's total, and 3.2% of the statewide total) and the Working Families line received 154,853 votes (5.3% and 3.4%), with the Democratic line receiving the remaining 2,610,220 votes (89.6% and 56.5%). The Conservative line received 232,281 votes (15.0% of Paladino's total, and 5.0% of the statewide total) and the Taxpayers line received 25,821 votes (1.5% and 0.6%), with the Republican line receiving the remaining 1,290,082 votes (83.3% and 27.1%).\n\n==== 2014 ====\n{{see also|2014 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo sought reelection in 2014, with former U.S. Representative Kathy Hochul as his new running mate. On March 5, 2014, [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[County Executive|County executive]] [[Rob Astorino]] announced that he would run on the Republican ticket against Cuomo for governor.<ref name=\"Astorino\">{{cite news|last=McKinley |first=Jesse | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/06/nyregion/astorino-bid-for-new-york-governor.html|title=Westchester Leader Opens Bid to Deny Cuomo a Second Term|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> Law professors [[Zephyr Teachout]] and [[Tim Wu]] challenged the Cuomo\u2013Hochul ticket in the Democratic primary election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.firedoglake.com/2014/09/10/cuomo-spent-nearly-40-times-more-than-teachout-to-win-primary/|title=Cuomo Spent Nearly 40 Times More Than Teachout To Win Primary|work=Shadowproof}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/election-night-stub/|title=Cuomo Wins Democratic Primary|publisher=WNYC}}</ref>\u2014capturing 34% of the vote on the gubernatorial line (Wu drew 40.1% as lieutenant governor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014-ny-state/|title=Election Results \u2013 2014 NY State Primary \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/zephyr-teachout-primary-loss-air-victory-party-article-1.1934371|title=Zephyr Teachout's primary election loss has air of a victory party, Annie Karni, NYTimes, 10 Sept. 2014|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, Cuomo was re-elected for a second term with 54% of the vote,<ref name=Kaplan141104>{{cite news |last=Kaplan |first=Thomas |date=November 4, 2014 |title=Andrew Cuomo Is Re-elected New York Governor, but Loses Clout |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-is-re-elected-governor-of-new-york.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=January 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Election-Day-2014-New-York-Governor-Andrew-Cuomo-Rob-Astorino-Vote-281478431.html|title=Andrew Cuomo Wins Re-election in NY Governor's Race|work=NBC New York}}</ref> while Astorino received 40.6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014/|title=Election 2014 \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = New York Democratic gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref name=primaryresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/Primary/2014StateLocalPrimaryElectionResults.pdf |title=2014 State Local Primary Results |publisher=New York State Board Of Elections |accessdate=October 25, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031122737/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/Primary/2014StateLocalPrimaryElectionResults.pdf |archivedate=October 31, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Andrew Cuomo\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 361,380\n| percentage = 62.92\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Zephyr Teachout]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 192,210\n| percentage = 33.47\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Randy Credico]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 20,760\n| percentage = 3.61\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 594,287\n| percentage= 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = New York Democratic lieutenant gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref name=primaryresults />\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kathy Hochul]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 329,089\n| percentage = 60.20\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Tim Wu]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 217,614\n| percentage = 39.80\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 546,703\n| percentage= 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nDespite a low voter turnout, Cuomo won the general election by a comfortable margin; however, his margin of victory was smaller than it had been in his 2010 victory. Astorino won most of upstate New York, but was overwhelmed in [[New York City]]. Cuomo was sworn in for second term as [[Governor]].\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | New York gubernatorial general election results, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyenr.elections.state.ny.us/|title=NYS Board of Elections Unofficial Election Night Results|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107220743/http://nyenr.elections.state.ny.us/|archivedate=November 7, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Running mate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Swing\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 1,811,672\n| align=\"right\" | 47.08%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 9.44%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#CC6699; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Working Families Party|Working Families]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 126,244\n| align=\"right\" | 3.22%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 0.13%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800080; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independence Party of New York|Independence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 77,762\n| align=\"right\" | 2.02%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 1.15%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E0218A; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Women's Equality Party (New York)|Women's Equality]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 53,802\n| align=\"right\" | 1.41%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| '''Andrew Cuomo'''\n| '''[[Kathy Hochul]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''2,069,480'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''54.19%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 8.86%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Rob Astorino''\n| align=\"right\" | 1,234,951\n| align=\"right\" | 32.59%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 4.65%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF8C00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Rob Astorino''\n| align=\"right\" | 250,634\n| align=\"right\" | 6.60%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 1.57%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#0F4D92; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Stop-Common-Core\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Rob Astorino''\n| align=\"right\" | 51,294\n| align=\"right\" | 1.39%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| [[Rob Astorino]]\n| Christopher Moss\n| align=\"right\" | 1,536,879\n| align=\"right\" | 40.24%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 6.71%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#0BDA51; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n| [[Howie Hawkins]]\n| Brian Jones\n| align=\"right\" | 184,419\n| align=\"right\" | 4.86%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 3.56%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Michael McDermott (politician)|Michael McDermott]]\n| Chris Edes\n| align=\"right\" | 16,967\n| align=\"right\" | 0.42%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 0.63%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#BCB88A; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Sapient\n| Steven Cohn\n| Bobby Kalotee\n| align=\"right\" | 4,963\n| align=\"right\" | 0.13%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | '' Scattering''\n| align=\"right\" | 6,378\n| align=\"right\" | 0.19%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.09%\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Majority'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''480,605'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''13.26%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 16.74%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''3,930,310'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.00%'''\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| colspan=\"7\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Hold'''\n|}\n\n==== 2018 ====\n{{main|2018 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo was challenged in the primary from the left by actress-and-activist [[Cynthia Nixon]]. She criticized him as having failed to fix the [[New York City Subway]] following his declaration of the [[2017 New York City transit crisis]], as well as his failure to protect undocumented immigrants, legalize recreational marijuana,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/cynthia-nixon-andrew-cuomo-debate-new-york-governor-1202921172/|title=Cynthia Nixon and Andrew Cuomo Spar Over Subway Woes, Legalizing Pot in Gubernatorial Debate|first=Cynthia|last=Littleton|date=August 30, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> or create a single payer healthcare system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-pol-nixon-cuomo-single-payer-health-care-20180724-story.html|title=Cynthia Nixon calls for single-payer health care in New York|last=Shittu|first=Kenneth Lovett, Esther|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> When debating Nixon, Cuomo countered her argument on the subways by pointing out that the system is owned by New York City, though past administrations agree it is the governor's role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/793250/andrew-cuomo-cynthia-nixon-gubernatorial-debate-gets-heated-stop-lying|title=Andrew Cuomo, Cynthia Nixon gubernatorial debate gets heated: 'Can you stop lying?'|date=August 29, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2018/08/31/cuomo-continues-his-ping-pong-approach-to-subway-ownership-588765|title=Cuomo continues his ping-pong approach to subway ownership|publisher=|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=gothamist>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2018/08/30/cuomo_corruption_questions.php|title=Some Questions For Cuomo After Wednesday's Debate|accessdate=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831110014/http://gothamist.com/2018/08/30/cuomo_corruption_questions.php|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An analysis conducted by New York City comptroller Scott Stringer revealed that New York City pays for 70 percent of subway repair costs.<ref name=gothamist />\n\nCuomo defeated Nixon, 65.53%-34.47%.\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=New York Democratic gubernatorial primary results, 2018<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2018/Primary/CertifiedResultsForSept13Primary.xlsx|title=Governor - Democratic - Primary September 13, 2018}}</ref>}}{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Andrew Cuomo (incumbent)|votes=1,021,160|percentage=65.53%}}{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Cynthia Nixon|votes=537,192|percentage=34.47%}}{{Election box total no change|votes=1,490,753|percentage=100%}}{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=New York Democratic lieutenant gubernatorial primary results, 2018<ref name=\"auto2\"/>}}{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Kathy Hochul (incumbent)|votes=733,591|percentage=53.3%}}{{Election box candidate with party link no change|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Jumaane Williams|votes=641,633|percentage=46.7%}}{{Election box total no change|votes=1,375,224|percentage=100%}}{{Election box end}}\n\nOn November 6, 2018, the Cuomo-Hochul ticket defeated the Molinaro-Killian ticket by a margin of 59.6%-36.2%.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2018/general/2018Governor.pdf|title=Certified Results from the November 6, 2018 General Election for Governor and Lt. Governor}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin\n| title=New York gubernatorial general election results, 2018<ref name=\"auto1\"/>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = ''3,424,416''\n  |percentage = ''56.16%''\n  |change     = ''+8.64%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Working Families Party\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = ''114,478''\n  |percentage = ''1.88%''\n  |change     = ''-1.43%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Independence Party of New York\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = ''68,713''\n  |percentage = ''1.13''%\n  |change     = ''-0.91%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Women's Equality Party (New York)\n  |candidate  = ''Andrew Cuomo''\n  |votes      = ''27,733''\n  |percentage = ''0.45%''\n  |change     = ''-0.96%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n| candidate  = {{nowrap|'''Andrew Cuomo/Kathy Hochul (incumbent)'''}}\n| party      = Total\n| votes      = '''3,635,340'''\n| percentage = '''59.62%'''\n| change     = '''+5.43%'''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = ''Marc Molinaro''\n  |votes      = ''1,926,485''\n  |percentage = ''31.60%''\n  |change     = ''-0.79%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party of New York State\n  |candidate  = ''Marc Molinaro''\n  |votes      = ''253,624''\n  |percentage = ''4.16%''\n  |change     = ''-2.41%''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Reform Party of New York State\n  |candidate  = ''Marc Molinaro''\n  |votes      = ''27,493''\n  |percentage = ''0.45%''\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n| candidate  = Marc Molinaro/Julie Killian\n| party      = Total\n| votes      = 2,207,602\n| percentage = 36.21%\n| change     = -4.10%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Green Party of New York\n  |candidate  = Howie Hawkins/Jia Lee\n  |votes      = 103,946\n  |percentage = 1.70%\n  |change     = -3.14%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Libertarian Party of New York\n  |candidate  = Larry Sharpe/Andrew Hollister\n  |votes      = 95,033\n  |percentage = 1.56%\n  |change     = +1.12%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Serve America Movement\n  |candidate  = Stephanie Miner/Michael Volpe\n  |votes      = 55,441\n  |percentage = 0.91%\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box total\n  |votes      = '''6,097,362'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n| winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\nCuomo took the gubernatorial oath of office at 12:01&nbsp;a.m. on January 1, 2011, succeeding David Paterson.<ref name=\"swearing_in\">{{cite news| first=Danny| last=Hakim| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/01/nyregion/01swearing.html |title=Cuomo Is Sworn In as New York's Governor|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 31, 2010|accessdate=January 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"swearing_in_2\">{{cite news|first=Jacob|last=Gershman|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704543604576054750661022820|title=Cuomo Takes Office, Calls New York State's Reputation a 'National Joke'|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 2, 2011|accessdate=January 11, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110126110737/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704543604576054750661022820.html| archivedate= January 26, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> During his first year as governor, Cuomo worked to pass an on-time budget<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/31/nyregion/31nybudget-albany.html | newspaper=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Kaplan | title=Albany Approves Budget, With Time to Spare | date=March 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/amazing_state_pols_ok_budget_on_9YH2yhLjFuFxF0ATtTcSII | work=New York Post | first1=Brendan | last1=Scott | first2=Fredric U. | last2=Dicker | title=Amazing! State pols OK budget on time | date=March 31, 2011}}</ref> that cut spending without raising taxes,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-03-27/local/29375758_1_new-york-state-budget-cuomo-spending-cuts | location=New York | work=Daily News | first1=Kenneth | last1=Lovett | first2=Glenn | last2=Blain | title=Cuomo, lawmakers reach New York State budget deal, agreeing on 2% cut in spending and no new taxes | date=March 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaltonight.com/2011/03/cuomo-victory-lap/ |title=Cuomo Praises Lawmakers In Video Victory Lap |publisher=Capitaltonight.com |date=March 31, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110412073005/http://www.capitaltonight.com/2011/03/cuomo-victory-lap/ |archivedate=April 12, 2011 }}</ref> made a new deal with a large state-employee union,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/04/nyregion/public-employees-union-accepts-cuomos-contract-deal-to-avert-layoffs.html | newspaper=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Kaplan | title=Public Employees Union Accepts Cuomo's Contract Deal to Avert Layoffs | date=November 3, 2011}}</ref> signed ethics reform legislation,<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamilton |first=Colby |url=http://empire.wnyc.org/2011/08/cuomo-signs-ethics-reform-into-law/ |title=Cuomo signs ethics reform into law \u2013 WNYC |publisher=Empire.wnyc.org |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> passed a property tax cap,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.ny.gov/press/6302011HistoricPropertyTaxCap |title=Governor Cuomo Signs Historic Property Tax Cap Legislation In Nassau County &#124; Governor Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Governor.ny.gov |date=June 30, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> worked to enact a same-sex marriage bill with bipartisan support,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/25/nation/la-na-gay-new-york-20110626 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Geraldine | last=Baum | title=Gay marriage fight shows N.Y. Gov. Andrew Cuomo is no rookie | date=June 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Chris |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intel/2011/06/gay_marriage_bill_all_goes_acc.html |title=Gay Marriage All Goes According to Andrew Cuomo's Plan \u2013 Daily Intel |work=New York |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> and restructured New York's tax code.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2011/12/assembly-finally-passes-tax-package | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Assembly (Finally) Passes Tax Package}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-12-06/news/30483620_1_tax-rate-tax-surcharge-tax-code | location=New York | work=Daily News | first=Kenneth | last=Lovett | title=Cuomo announces sweeping tax deal | date=December 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bill Clinton, Bob Castelli, Andrew Cuomo.JPG|thumb|Former president of the United States [[Bill Clinton]] (left) and Cuomo in 2012]]\nThere was media speculation about a possible presidential run, either in 2016 or 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0611/57765.html |title=Andrew Cuomo 2016 speculation heating up \u2013 Edward-Isaac Dovere and Maggie Haberman |publisher=Politico.Com |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo jumpstarts 2016 speculation |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/national/politico/article/Cuomo-jumpstarts-2016-speculation-1440448.php |date=June 25, 2011 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer }}</ref> Several reports indicated that Cuomo supported the [[Independent Democratic Conference]] until its dissolution and defeat in 2018 in part to appear more moderate for an eventual presidential bid.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Cuomo noninterference story falls apart |publisher=Politico |last=Zeff |first=Blake |date=September 2, 2016 |accessdate=January 18, 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2016/05/another-cuomo-noninterference-story-falls-apart-049022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/9/13/17854554/andrew-cuomo-new-york-president-2020-no |title=Andrew Cuomo has won himself another term, but his presidential aspirations are dead |first=Matthew |last=Yglesias |publisher=Vox |date=September 14, 2018 |accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/09/13/new-york-democratic-primary-cuomo-idc/ |first=Eoin |last=Higgins |date=September 13, 2018 |title=A group of Democrats joined Republicans to give them power in New York. On Election Day, New Yorkers wiped them out.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=The New Republic |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/142670/andrew-cuomo-profits-republican-senate |title=How Andrew Cuomo Profits From a Republican Senate |first1=Alex |last1=Shephard |first2=Clio |last2=Chang |date=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor his 2018 re-election bid, Cuomo accepted being on top of the ballot line for the Independence Party, a list that featured numerous Republicans, including ardent Trump supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/01/nyregion/cuomo-independence-line-ballot-governor-election.html |title=Third-Party Line Will Feature Governor Cuomo, and a Slew of Republicans |newspaper=New York Times |access-date=2018-08-01 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn an August 15, 2018, anti-sex trafficking bill-signing event, Cuomo said: \"We're not gonna make America great again. It was never that great. We have not reached greatness. We will reach greatness when every American is fully engaged.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/cuomo-america-was-never-that-great/ar-BBLYIOW?OCID=ansmsnnews11|title=Cuomo: America 'was never that great'|website=Msn.com|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref> The assembled audience of Cuomo's supporters booed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-media-keep-falling-into-the-trump-trap-1534892905|title=Opinion - The Media Keep Falling Into the Trump Trap |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |first=Jason L. |last=Riley |date=August 21, 2018 |accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2019 [[opinion poll]], Cuomo's approval rating dropped to 43 percent, the lowest of his tenure as governor, and a full 50% said they disapproved.<ref>[https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/politics/albany/2019/02/11/andrew-cuomos-popularity-hits-low-poll-siena-abortion-new-york/2833906002/ Gov. Andrew Cuomo's popularity hits new low, poll says] 11 February 2019. Democrat and Chronicle.</ref> The poll showed an eight percent drop from January 2019; it was taken after Cuomo signed several pieces of progressive legislation, including an [[Reproductive Health Act|expansion of abortion in New York]] and stricter gun laws, suggesting that the legislation may have upset certain voters and contributed to the drop.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/11/nyregion/cuomo-siena-poll-approval-rating.html Cuomo's Approval Rating Drops to Lowest Level in 8 Years as Governor] 11 February 2019. The New York Times.</ref>\n\n==== Coronavirus response ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)}}\nIn 2020, Cuomo received widespread praise from epidemiologists for his handling of the evolving COVID-19 pandemic in New York State which includes a state-wide lockdown and a shutdown of non-essential businesses in an effort to help [[Social distancing|flatten the curve]] of the virus. Like many other national leaders, however, Cuomo also received criticism for apparently failing to grasp the gravity of the pandemic before its risks were fully visible to the American public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/20/coronavirus-in-ny-cuomo-orders-lockdown-shuts-down-non-essential-businesses/|title=Coronavirus in NY: Cuomo orders lockdown, shuts down non-essential businesses|last=Hogan|first=Bernadette|last2=Marsh|first2=Julia|date=2020-03-20|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|last3=Hicks|first3=Nolan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/coronavirus-crisis-cuomo-trump-show-leadership-contrast-n1166066|title=Analysis: Cuomo and Trump show coronavirus crisis leadership contrast|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2020, Cuomo threatened [[Rhode Island]] with a lawsuit over a new state [[quarantine]] policy of stopping incoming New Yorkers to enforce quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue RI over new policy to find New Yorkers in the state |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/490019-cuomo-threatens-to-sue-ri-over-new-coronavirus-policy-targeting-ny |work=The Hill |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cuomo threatens to sue Rhode Island if it doesn't ease up on New Yorkers during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/905509/cuomo-threatens-sue-rhode-island-doesnt-ease-new-yorkers-during-coronavirus-pandemic |work=The Week |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Corporate incentives ====\nCuomo has supported providing tax and other incentives to attract business to locate in New York State.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-launches-new-york-open-business-marketing-initiative| title=Governor Cuomo Launches \"New York Open for Business\" Marketing Initiative| accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bizjournals.com/albany/morning_call/2015/08/cuomo-says-ny-tax-incentives-are-a-necessity.html| title=Cuomo says New York tax incentives are a necessity for attracting businesses| accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> {{anchor|Amazon Cuomo}} He even joked in 2018 that he would be willing to change his name to \"Amazon Cuomo\" if [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] located their \"[[Amazon HQ2]]\" in the state.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-governor-jokes-amazon-cuomo-name-change-hq2-2018-11| work=Business Insider|title=New York's governor jokes he'll change his name to 'Amazon Cuomo' to win the HQ2 bid hours before a report that New York City will be home to one of the company's new headquarters| accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> His strong support for New York City's bid to become the home of Amazon's HQ2 faced criticism based on arguments that the costs to the state outweighed the possible benefits.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.governing.com/gov-institute/voices/col-tax-incentives-hidden-costs-business-friendly-policies.html| title=Tax Incentives' Bipartisan Folly| accessdate=13 November 2018|website=Governing.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://nypost.com/2018/10/31/cuomos-amazon-offer-is-a-sick-joke-on-new-york/| title=Cuomo's Amazon offer is a sick joke on New York|work=New York Post |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> Amazon decided on two \"major corporate outposts\" in New York City and [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington, Virginia]]\u2014instead of a single second headquarters.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/13/technology/amazon-hq2-headquarters.html| title=Amazon Announces New York and Virginia as HQ2 Picks|work=The New York Times| accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Criminal justice ====\nIn August 2017, the Cuomo administration awarded more than $7 million - financed with money from large bank settlements - in grants to New York colleges to offer courses to New York prisoners.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/06/nyregion/cuomo-to-give-colleges-7-million-for-courses-in-prisons.html|title=Cuomo to Give Colleges $7 Million for Courses in Prisons|last=McKinley|first=Jesse|date=2017-08-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In January 2018, Cuomo proposed reforms that would \"reduce delays during trials, ban asset seizures in cases where there has been no conviction and make it easier for former convicts to get a job after leaving prison.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/02/nyregion/cuomo-ending-cash-bail-state-of-the-state.html|title=Cuomo, in Bid to Help Poor, Proposes Ending Cash Bail for Minor Crimes|last=McKinley|first=James C., Jr.|date=2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also called for an end to cash bail for minor crimes.<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\nUnder Cuomo's tenure, he granted commutations to fewer prisoners than many previous Republican and Democratic New York governors.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://theappeal.org/cuomo-the-merciless/|title=Cuomo the Merciless|work=The Appeal|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en}}</ref> Cuomo commuted a total of nine sentences.<ref name=\":7\" /> Cuomo pardoned 140 adults who were convicted of nonviolent felonies as 16- and 17-year-olds, but had served their sentences.<ref name=\":7\" /> He pardoned 18 others who had served their sentences for nonviolent felonies but were exposed to deportation due to their criminal record.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n[[File:Andrew Cuomo at March For Our Lives rally.jpg|thumb|Cuomo leading the 2018 New York City [[March For Our Lives]] rally]]\n\n==== Gun control ====\nOn January 15, 2013, Cuomo signed into law the first state [[gun control]] bill to pass after the December 14, 2012, [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] in neighboring Connecticut.<ref name=Glaser130115>{{cite news |last=Glaser |first=Howard |date=January 15, 2013 |title=Cuomo Gun Safety Legislation Passes NY State Senate With Bipartisan Support, Assembly Action Today |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/howard-glaser/cuomo-gun-safety-legislation_b_2476419.html |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> The [[NY SAFE Act]] was described as the toughest gun control law in the United States.<ref name=Walshe130115>{{cite news |last=Walshe |first=Shushannah |date=January 15, 2013 |title=New York Passes Nation's Toughest Gun-Control Law |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/york-state-passes-toughest-gun-control-law-nation/story?id=18224091 |accessdate=January 16, 2013 |publisher=[[ABC News]] }}</ref> The act came under criticism, and the [[National Rifle Association]] called it draconian. The New York State Sheriffs' Association issued a statement supporting tougher penalties for illegal use of firearms, but criticizing several aspects of the legislation, including a magazine limit of seven rounds and a \"too broad\" definition of assault weapons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sheriff's response to NY SAFE Act |url=http://www.nysheriffs.org/articles/sheriffs%E2%80%99-response-ny-safe-act |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129224050/http://www.nysheriffs.org/articles/sheriffs%E2%80%99-response-ny-safe-act |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-29 |publisher=New York State Sheriff's Association }}</ref>\n\nOn July 5, 2013, Cuomo signed an amendment to the NY SAFE Act that exempts retired police officers from some of the act's ownership restrictions.<ref name=Weaver130715>{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Teri |date=July 15, 2013 |title=Gov. Andrew Cuomo signs amendment to NY Safe Act allowing exceptions for retired police |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/07/gov_andrew_cuomo_signs_amendment_to_ny_safe_act_allowing_exceptions_for_retired.html |newspaper=The Post-Standard |location=Syracuse, New York |accessdate=July 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==== Hurricane Sandy ====\n[[File:B&T 3604 (8139739680).jpg|thumb|Cuomo in New York City in October 2012]]\nAfter [[Hurricane Sandy]] in October 2012, Cuomo allowed New York voters, via a specific provision aimed at accommodating those displaced, to cast provisional ballots for the 2012 election anywhere in New York state.<ref name=\"NYTimes110512\">{{cite news |author1=David Halbfinger |author2=Thomas Kaplan |author3=Wendy Ruderman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/06/nyregion/after-hurricane-sandy-efforts-to-help-the-displaced-vote.html |title=Officials Rush to Find Ways for the Storm-Tossed to Vote |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 5, 2012 |accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref> He also appointed a [[Moreland Commission|commission]] to examine the responses of New York utilities to damage caused by the storm.<ref name=\"NYT_Moreland\">{{cite news |title=Suffering on Long Island as Power Agency Shows Its Flaws |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/14/nyregion/long-island-power-authoritys-flaws-hindered-recovery-efforts.html |work=The New York Times |date=November 13, 2012 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nControversy ensued when the Cuomo administration used $140 million, including $40 million of federal disaster relief funds, to pay for the broadcast of national TV ads promoting \"New New York\" slogans outside New York in an attempt to attract new business investment to the state.<ref name=\"adcampaign\">{{cite news|last=Hakim|first=Danny|title=Ad Effort Selling State as a Business Haven Is Criticized|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/04/nyregion/new-york-states-ads-to-attract-business-also-draw-complaints.html|accessdate= June 4, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Eliana|title=Andrew Cuomo Launches Ad Campaign to Lure Businesses to N.Y.|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/347489/andrew-cuomo-launches-ad-campaign-lure-businesses-ny|accessdate= June 4, 2013|newspaper=The National Review|date=May 6, 2013}}</ref> Many have been critical of the effort, including former New York governor [[Eliot Spitzer]], who called the ads \"fluff\" and \"a waste of taxpayer money\".<ref name=\"adcampaign\" />\n\n==== Hydraulic fracturing ====\nIn June 2012, the Cuomo administration said it was considering lifting a state ban on the practice of [[hydraulic fracturing]] (also known as \"fracking\")<ref name=nym>{{cite news|url=https://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/topic/fracking-2012-9/|title=Fracklash|work=New York|date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> to stimulate the economy in [[upstate New York]]. But critics said that fracking in Upstate New York could contaminate the water supply of New York City, New Jersey and parts of Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nofracking.com/|title=Stop fracking, and save our water, land, and air!|date=September 16, 2014|publisher=nofracking.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/local/2014/02/18/hearing-on-ny-energy-plan-attracts-fracking-critics/5589917/|title=Hearing on NY energy plan attracts fracking critics|date=February 18, 2014|publisher=Democrat & Chronicle|author=Campbell, J.}}</ref> Following a long-awaited study started years earlier, New York State health officials cited \"significant public health risks\" associated with fracking, and on December 17, 2014, the Cuomo administration announced a ban on hydraulic fracturing in New York State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/nyregion/cuomo-to-ban-fracking-in-new-york-state-citing-health-risks.html|title=Citing Health Risks, Cuomo Bans Fracking in New York State|date=December 17, 2014|work=The New York Times|author= Kaplan, Thomas.}}</ref>\n\n==== Independent Democratic Conference (IDC) ====\nIn 2014, Politico reported that Cuomo had been actively involved in the formation of the [[Independent Democratic Conference]] three years earlier, which gave control of the state senate to Republicans.<ref name=\"idc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2016/05/another-cuomo-noninterference-story-falls-apart-049022|title=Another Cuomo noninterference story falls apart|last1=Zeff|first1=Blake|publisher=Politico|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> He has been accused of failing to bridge the rift between the IDC and the Democratic caucus in the Senate despite being able to.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/09/nyregion/cuomo-stewart-cousins-new-york-senate-democrats.html|title=Tensions Flare as Cuomo Confronts Democratic Rift|last1=Goldmacher|first1=Shane|date=9 August 2017|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\nIn solidarity with [[Israel]], Cuomo announced an executive order against the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] movement. Cuomo tweeted: \"If you boycott Israel, New York State will boycott you.\"<ref name=\"boycott\"/>\n\n====Medical marijuana====\nIn January 2014, Cuomo announced <ref name=\"announced\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/05/nyregion/new-york-state-is-set-to-loosen-marijuana-laws.html|title=New York State Is Set to Loosen Marijuana Laws|last=Craig|first=Susanne|date=January 4, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref> the introduction of a [[medical marijuana]] bill. In July of that year, New York became the 23rd state<ref name=\"medical marijuana\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/07/07/health/new-york-medical-marijuana/|title=New York legalizes medical marijuana|last=Ferrigno|first=Lorenzo|date=September 11, 2014|work=[[CNN]] |accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref> to allow the medical use of marijuana when Cuomo signed the Compassionate Care Act.<ref name=\"Compasionate Care Act\">{{cite web|url=http://marijuanareform.org/marijuana-legalization-in-new-york/|title=Marijuana Legalization in the New York|date=September 28, 2014|work=[[Marijuana Reform Party|New York]]|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== New York City Subway ====\n{{Main|2017 New York City transit crisis}}\n[[File:Inaugural ride of the Second Avenue Subway (31224282093).jpg|thumb|The inaugural ride of the [[Second Avenue Subway]] was led by Cuomo on December 31, 2016]]\nIn June 2017, after a series of subway disasters, Cuomo declared a \"state of emergency\" for the [[New York City Subway]] system.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/18/nyregion/new-york-subway-system-failure-delays.html|title=How Politics and Bad Decisions Starved New York's Subways|last=Rosenthal|first=Brian M.|date=2017-11-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-29|last2=Fitzsimmons|first2=Emma G.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=LaForgia|first3=Michael}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', a series of New York City mayors and New York governors, including Cuomo, were partly at fault for the worsening quality of the subway system and inflated construction costs.<ref name=\":2\" /> Under the Cuomo administration, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] repeatedly diverted tax revenues earmarked for the subways, paid for services that there was no need for and spent on subway projects that did not boost service or reliability.<ref name=\":2\" /> As a result, the MTA was saddled with debt and could not undertake investments into overhauling outdated and inefficient subway infrastructure.<ref name=\":2\" /> Cuomo also directed the MTA to spend on projects that the heads of the MTA did not consider to be priorities.<ref name=\":2\" /> One reason why the New York City subway system is so expensive is due to exorbitant labor costs; according to several M.T.A. officials who were involved in negotiating labor contracts, Cuomo pressured the MTA to accept labor union contracts that were extremely favorable to workers.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''The New York Times'' noted that Cuomo was closely aligned with the union in question and had received $165,000 in campaign contributions from the union.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n''The New York Times'' reported, \"Cuomo had steered clear of the M.T.A. during his first years in office, but in his second term he took an intense interest. He placed aides within the organization and, in an unusual move, made some report directly to him. He badgered transit leaders about the construction of the [[Second Avenue Subway|Second Avenue subway]] on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. And over the objections of some board members, he canceled several M.T.A. capital projects to make room for his own priorities. According to high-ranking current and former M.T.A. officials, the moves interfered with the authority's plans to address the rising delays.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Official corruption ====\nIn July 2014, it was reported that the [[Moreland Commission to Investigate Public Corruption|Moreland Commission]], a committee established by Cuomo to root out corruption in politics, was directed away from investigations that could be politically damaging.<ref name=\"moreland\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/23/nyregion/governor-andrew-cuomo-and-the-short-life-of-the-moreland-commission.html|title=Cuomo's Office Hobbled Ethics Inquiries by Moreland Commission|last=Craig|first=Susanne|date=July 24, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> Cuomo later abruptly and controversially disbanded the commission.<ref name=\"moreland\" /> Federal prosecutors in Manhattan launched an inquiry into Cuomo's dealings with the anticorruption panel and concluded that \"after a thorough investigation,\" there was \"insufficient evidence to prove a federal crime.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/12/nyregion/in-moreland-commission-inquiry-insufficient-evidence-to-prove-a-crime.html|title=Cuomo Won't Face Federal Charges Over Moreland Ethics Panel|last=Weiser|first=Benjamin|date=2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Joseph Percoco, a close friend and former top aide to Cuomo, was indicted as part of a bribery investigation into the [[Buffalo Billion]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/23/nyregion/cuomo-former-aides-charges.html|title=Ex-Cuomo Aides Charged in Federal Corruption Inquiry|last=Yee|first=William K. Rashbaum, Vivian|date=September 23, 2016|last2=Weiser|first2=Benjamin|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 22, 2016|page=A1}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://observer.com/2016/09/all-the-governors-men-federal-charges-against-top-cuomo-aide-donor-and-suny-head/|title=All the Governor's Men\u2014Federal Charges Against Top Cuomo Aide, Donor and SUNY Head|date=September 22, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"blog.timesunion.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.timesunion.com/capitol/archives/267664/who-is-joe-percoco-former-cuomo-aide-charged-by-bharara-thursday/|title=Who is Joe Percoco, former Cuomo aide charged by Bharara Thursday?|date=September 22, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Percoco had worked for Cuomo in both Washington and Albany and had managed his 2010 and 2014 gubernatorial campaigns. he has been described as \"the governor's enforcer and a member of his inner circle\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/politics/politics-on-the-hudson/2018/09/20/andrew-cuomo-aide-joe-percoco-sentenced-6-years-prison/1368203002/|title=Joe Percoco, Andrew Cuomo's former right-hand man, gets 6 years in prison|first1=Jon|last1=Campbell|first2=Jonathan|last2=Bandler|website=lohud.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.timesunion.com/capitol/archives/267664/who-is-joe-percoco-former-cuomo-aide-charged-by-bharara-thursday/|title=Who is Joe Percoco, former Cuomo aide charged by Bharara Thursday?|first1=Matthew Hamilton on|last1=September 22|first2=2016 at 8:53|last2=AM|date=September 22, 2016|website=Capitol Confidential}}</ref> Cuomo had previously referred to Percoco as a brother, and as Mario Cuomo's \"third son\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/politics/politics-on-the-hudson/2018/03/13/percoco-verdict-reached-trial-cuomo/420236002/|title=Joe Percoco, ex-aide to Cuomo, guilty of 3 felonies in bribery case|first1=Jon|last1=Campbell|first2=Joseph|last2=Spector|website=lohud.com}}</ref> Todd Howe, a lobbyist and former Cuomo aide, was also indicted, along with several developers who were major donors to Cuomo and other state politicians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Cuomo was not accused of wrongdoing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"blog.timesunion.com\" /> In March 2018, a federal jury in Manhattan convicted Percoco on felony charges of solicitation of bribes and [[honest services fraud]] for over $315,000 in bribes he took from two people seeking official favors on behalf of an energy company, Competitive Power Ventures Inc. Prosecutors framed Percoco as Cuomo's \"right-hand man.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eenews.net/energywire/2018/03/14/stories/1060076267|title=Jury finds former Cuomo aide guilty of gas deal corruption|last=Rahim|first=Saqib|date=2018-03-14|work=Energy Wire|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Vivian|last2=Weiser|first2=Benjamin|title=Joseph Percoco, Ex-Cuomo Aide, Found Guilty in Corruption Trial|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/13/nyregion/percoco-corruption-bribery-trial-cuomo-guilty.html|accessdate=15 March 2018|work=The New York Times|date=14 March 2018|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Joseph Percoco, Former Executive Aide And Campaign Manager To N.Y. Governor, Convicted Of Accepting More Than $300,000 In Bribes|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/joseph-percoco-former-executive-aide-and-campaign-manager-ny-governor-convicted|accessdate=15 March 2018|work=13 March 2018|agency=[[United States Department of Justice]]|issue=180-74|language=en}}</ref> Following Percoco's conviction, Cuomo released a statement declaring that he would respect the jury's verdict and that \"there is no tolerance for any violation of the public trust.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/13/nyregion/percoco-corruption-bribery-trial-cuomo-guilty.html|title=Joseph Percoco, Ex-Cuomo Aide, Found Guilty in Corruption Trial|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nystateofpolitics.com/2018/03/cuomo-reacts-to-percoco-verdict/|title=Cuomo Reacts To Percoco Verdict|website=Nystateofpolitics.com|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/news/region-state/percoco-conviction-hurts-cuomo-1.17372930|title=Percoco conviction hurts Cuomo, observers say|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Public college and university tuition ====\nOn April 18, 2017, Cuomo signed the New York State 2018 fiscal year budget. It included the [[Excelsior Scholarship]], a provision that families making less than $125,000 in 2019 could have free tuition at all [[State University of New York|SUNY]] and [[City University of New York|CUNY]] universities,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/11/nyregion/new-yorks-free-tuition-program-will-help-traditional-but-not-typical-students.html|title=New York's Free-Tuition Program Will Help Traditional, but Not Typical, Students|last=Chen|first=David W.|date=2017-04-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-13|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ny.gov/programs/tuition-free-degree-program-excelsior-scholarship|title=Tuition-Free Degree Program: The Excelsior Scholarship|date=2016-12-27|work=Welcome to the State of New York|access-date=2017-04-13|language=en}}</ref> though some education experts including [[Sara Goldrick-Rab]]&nbsp;say it won't help the poorest students and that the requirement that recipients live and work in New York after graduating is counter-productive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shakingnews.com/blog/2017/04/13/free-college-whats-catch-excelsior-scholarship/|title=Free College? What's the Catch with the Excelsior Scholarship? - ShakingNews|date=2017-04-13|work=ShakingNews|access-date=2017-04-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Public employees ====\nOn July 16, 2011, Cuomo finalized a five-year deal with the Public Employees Federation to end pay raises, implement furlough days, and require additional contributions to health insurance accounts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaplan|first=Thomas|title=Union Yields on Benefits in Deal With Cuomo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/17/nyregion/to-save-jobs-union-approves-big-concessions-in-deal-with-cuomo.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 17, 2011|pages=A16}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'', Cuomo stated his top goal in 2012 is the reduction of [[Public employee pension plans in the United States|public employee pensions]].<ref name=\"NYT interview\">{{cite news|last=Kaplan|first=Thomas|last2=Barbaro|first2=Michael|title=Cuomo Says Curbing Public Pension Benefits Will Be His Top Goal in '12|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/14/nyregion/cuomo-says-he-wants-to-tackle-pension-changes-in-2012.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 14, 2011|pages=A20}}</ref>\n\n==== Public housing ====\nIn the winter of 2018, Cuomo responded to a class-action lawsuit brought against the [[New York City Housing Authority]] by attorney [[Jim Walden (lawyer)|Jim Walden]] on behalf of a group of public housing tenants. The suit was the first of its kind and called upon NYCHA to immediately address decrepit and unhealthy conditions in public housing units across New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/27/nyregion/nycha-lawsuit-nyc-housing.html|title=Tenants Sue New York City Housing Authority: 'We Have Let Other People Speak for Us for Too Long'|last=Mays|first=Jeffery C.|date=2018-02-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the invitation of Walden, Cuomo toured a public housing project in March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2018/03/11/cuomo-to-meet-nycha-tenants-after-declaring-emergency/|title=Cuomo to meet NYCHA tenants after declaring emergency|date=2018-03-11|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref> By early April, Cuomo appointed an independent monitor to oversee NYCHA on an emergency basis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/02/nyregion/cuomo-nycha-state-of-emergency.html|title=Cuomo Creates Monitor to Oversee Repairs to City's Public Housing|last=Ferr\u00e9-Sadurn\u00ed|first=Luis|date=2018-04-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-10|last2=Goodman|first2=J. David|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The move broadened the ever-widening rift between NYC mayor [[Bill de Blasio|Bill DeBlasio]] and Cuomo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2018/03/21/de-blasio-blasts-cuomo-over-visit-to-nycha-building/|title=De Blasio blasts Cuomo over visit to NYCHA building|date=2018-03-21|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/05/de-blasio-cuomo-is-no-white-knight-for-nycha/|title=De Blasio: Cuomo is no 'white knight' for NYCHA|date=2018-04-05|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Same-sex marriage ====\n[[File:Andrew Cuomo 2013.jpg|thumb|Cuomo at [[NYC Pride March]] in 2013]]\nIn keeping with a campaign promise, Cuomo signed same-sex marriage legislation on June 24, 2011, following an \"intense public and private lobbying campaign\", and later called for all states to do the same.<ref name=\"GayMarriage\">{{cite news |first=Reid |last=Epstein |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0611/57749.html |title=Cuomo signs New York gay marriage bill |work=[[Politico]] |date=June 24, 2011 |accessdate=July 6, 2011}}</ref> Cuomo was lauded for his efforts to pass same-sex marriage legislation.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/gov-andrew-cuomo-honored-empire-state-pride-agenda-key-gay-marriage-figures-missing-article-1.967831 | location=New York | work=Daily News | title=Gossip}}</ref><ref name=\"kaplan1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/02/nyregion/cuomo-fund-fills-with-money-from-thankful-gay-donors.html | newspaper=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Kaplan | title=Cuomo Fund Fills With Money From Thankful Gay Donors | date=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"kaplan2\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/28/nyregion/gov-andrew-m-cuomo-calls-for-same-sex-marriage-in-all-states.html | newspaper=The New York Times | first=Thomas | last=Kaplan | title=Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo Calls for Same-Sex Marriage in All States | date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> One prominent advocate stated that \"for gay Americans, Mr. Cuomo was \"the only national politician with hero status.\"<ref name=\"kaplan1\" /> Following the passage of the Marriage Equality Act, Cuomo was criticized for describing the viewpoints of same-sex marriage opponents as being \"anti-American.\"<ref name=\"TheAdvocate022212\">{{cite news |first=Julie |last=Bolcer |url=http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2011/10/25/Gay_Marriage_Opponents_Want_Apology_from_Cuomo/ |title=Gay Marriage Opponents Want Apology from Cuomo |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=October 25, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://polhudson.lohudblogs.com/2011/12/09/burling-cuomo-doesnt-scare-me/ |title=Burling: Cuomo \"Doesn't Scare Me\" &#124; Politics on the Hudson |publisher=Polhudson.lohudblogs.com |date=December 9, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> On July 25, 2011, a lawsuit was filed in the [[New York Supreme Court]] seeking an injunction against the Marriage Equality Act, alleging corruption and violations of the law in the process of passing the bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/07/25/new.york.gay.marriage.lawsuit/ |title=Lawsuit filed over New York same-sex marriage law |publisher=CNN |date=July 25, 2011 |accessdate=December 5, 2011}}</ref> The trial court initially held that the plaintiffs' case could proceed, but the decision was reversed on appeal.<ref>[https://www.leagle.com/decision/innyco20120706277 New Yorkers for Constitutional Freedoms v. New York State Senate], 98 A.D.3d 285, 297, 948 N.Y.S.2d 787, 797 leave to appeal denied, 19 N.Y.3d 814, 979 N.E.2d 813 (2012)</ref>\n\nCuomo ordered a boycott of [[Indiana]] and [[North Carolina]] to protest their [[LGBT rights by country or territory|anti-LGBT laws]].<ref name=\"boycott\">{{cite news |title=In Case Brought by School Speech Pathologist, Texas Federal Court Becomes the Third to Strike Down Pro-Israel Oath as Unconstitutional |url=https://theintercept.com/2019/04/26/in-case-brought-by-school-speech-pathologist-texas-federal-court-becomes-the-third-to-strike-down-pro-israel-oath-as-unconstitutional/ |work=The Intercept |date=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== START-UP NY ====\nIn July 2016, the Empire State Development Corporation, a state agency, released a report indicating that the state's flagship business tax incentive program, called START-UP NY, had generated 408 jobs since its inception in 2014. Ads promoting the program have cost at least $53 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/local/2015/04/07/watchdog-start-ny-ads-cost-taxpayers/25429449/|title=Watchdog: Start-Up NY ads cost taxpayers $53M|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref> The START-UP NY annual report was delayed three months in 2016, leading some lawmakers, such as Assemblyman Schimminger, to call the delays \"curious\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2016/08/cuomos-economic-development-chief-defiantly-faces-down-start-up-ny-questions-104467|title=Cuomo economic development chief responds defiantly to Start-Up NY questions|access-date=September 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Taxes ====\nCuomo was praised for his 2011 restructuring of the New York State tax code.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.timesunion.com/capitol/archives/93839/tax-code-agreement-react-o-mat/ |title=Capitol Confidential \u00bb Tax code agreement React-O-Mat |publisher=Blog.timesunion.com |date=December 6, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.norwoodnews.org/id=5056&story=bronx-pols-get-behind-cuomos-tax-plan/ |title=Bronx Pols Get Behind Cuomo's Tax Plan |publisher=Norwood News |date=December 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2011/12/governor_andrew_cuomo_hears_ho.html |title=Governor Andrew Cuomo hears hosannas for New York deal on tax reform |publisher=SILive.com |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> He was also criticized for including tax increases for high earners,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/opinion/opedcolumnists/andrew_lip_service_yJpWH4ySvPeGnFzqRDGNTL | work=New York Post | first=E.J. | last=McMahon | title=Andrew's lip service | date=December 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes120611\" /> and for allegedly requesting a unanimous Assembly vote in favor of the proposal and threatening to campaign against Assembly members who voted \"no\"<ref name=\"timesunion1\">{{cite web|last=Vielkind|first=Jimmy |url=http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Governor-to-Assembly-GOP-Vote-for-tax-code-2391075.php |title=Governor to Assembly GOP: Vote for tax code unanimously or risk seats |publisher=Times Union |date=December 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> \u2013 a charge he denied.<ref name=\"timesunion1\" /> Cuomo also received criticism from voices on the left who felt that the tax reform was insufficient.<ref name=\"NYTimes120611\">{{cite news |first=Thomas |last=Kaplan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/07/nyregion/cuomo-and-legislative-leaders-agree-on-tax-deal.html |title=Albany Tax Deal to Raise Rate for Highest Earners |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 6, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== Voting rights ====\nIn April 2018, Cuomo announced that he would restore the voting rights of parolees through an executive order.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/nyregion/felons-pardon-voting-rights-cuomo.html|title=Cuomo Plans to Restore Voting Rights to Paroled Felons|last=Wang|first=Vivian|date=2018-04-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Cuomo said that he would consider restoring the voting rights of all parolees (more than 35,000), and would also enfranchise new parolees throughout his term.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==== Women's issues and abortion ====\nIn 2013, Cuomo called for the passage of a Women's Equality Act.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/transcript-governor-andrew-m-cuomos-2013-state-state-address | title=Transcript of Governor Andrew M. Cuomo's 2013 State of the State Address | accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The Women's Equality Act included 10 component bills affecting issues such as domestic violence, human trafficking, and pregnancy discrimination.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The tenth bill of the Women's Equality Act was the Reproductive Health Act,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nysenate.gov/legislation/bills/2013/s438 | title=Reproductive Health Act | accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> which would have \"enshrine[d] in state law existing federal protections for abortion rights,\" \"shift[ed] the state's abortion law from the criminal code to the health care laws,\" and \"[made] it clearer that licensed health care practitioners as well as physicians could perform abortions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/20/opinion/strengthening-reproductive-rights-in-new-york.html | work=New York Times | title=Reproductive Rights in New York | date=February 19, 2013 | accessdate= January 6, 2018}}</ref> During his 2013 State of the State address, Cuomo said, \"Enact a Reproductive Health Act because it is her body, it is her choice. Because it's her body, it's her choice. Because it's her body, it's her choice.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> The New York State Assembly passed the Women's Equality Act on June 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://assembly.state.ny.us/Press/20130620d/|title=Refusing to Shatter Women's Equality into Parts, Assembly Approves All 10 Points of Women's Equality Act|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref> The Republican leadership of the New York State Senate expressed support for the nine non-abortion-related planks of the Women's Equality Act, but objected to the Reproductive Health Act and expressed unwillingness to allow a vote on it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/officially-gov-cuomo-ny-senate-gop-dig-heels-women-equality-act-blog-entry-1.1695125 | title=Officially, Gov. Cuomo, NY Senate GOP Dig In Their Heels On Women's Equality Act |last=Katz |first=Celeste | date=June 19, 2013 |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the final day of the 2013 legislative session, following the Senate Republican Conference's continued refusal to vote on the full Women's Equality Act, Senator Jeff Klein, leader of the Independent Democratic Conference (IDC), offered the abortion plank of the Act as a hostile amendment to another bill.<ref name=\"State of Politics\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nystateofpolitics.com/2013/06/klein-offers-hostile-abortion-amendment-fails/| title=Klein Offers Hostile Abortion Amendment, Fails (Updatedx2)|work = State of Politics | date=June 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The amendment was defeated by a narrow margin of 32-31; all 30 Senate Republicans voted against the abortion amendment, as did Democratic Sens. Ruben Diaz and Simcha Felder.<ref name=\"State of Politics\"/> The Senate proceeded to pass the nine non-abortion-related planks of the Women's Equality Act as separate bills, and the 2013 legislative session came to an end without any portion of the WEA becoming law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assembly.state.ny.us/Press/20130620d|title=Senate Approves Women Equality Agenda|date=June 21, 2013|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"[After] the 2014 election season was over, with Cuomo victorious, the governor and his lieutenant governor Kathy Hochul both declared the abortion plank of the act officially dormant, if not dead.\"<ref name=\"Nahmias\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2015/06/quietly-most-of-womens-equality-act-becomes-law-023451| title=Quietly, most of Women's Equality Act becomes law |last=Nahmias |first=Laura | date=June 30, 2015 |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In 2015, the non-abortion-related Women's Equality Act bills passed both houses of the State Legislature.<ref name=\"Nahmias\"/> In October 2015, Cuomo signed eight of the 10 Women's Equality Act bills into law; the abortion rights bill was not among them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Cuomo-signs-women-s-equality-bills-6583054.php| title=Cuomo signs women's equality bills |last=Hamilton |first=Matthew | work = Times Union | date=October 21, 2015 |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2019, Cuomo signed the 2019 version of the [[Reproductive Health Act]], which passed days after Democrats took control of the state Senate.<ref name=\"BN12219\">[https://buffalonews.com/2019/01/22/long-stalled-abortion-bill-passes-new-york-legislature/ Long-stalled abortion bill passes New York Legislature] (The Buffalo News)</ref> Cuomo ordered [[One World Trade Center]] and other landmarks to be lit in pink to celebrate the bill's passage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/news/governor-cuomo-directs-one-world-trade-center-and-other-landmarks-be-lit-pink-celebrate-signing|title=Governor Cuomo Directs One World Trade Center and Other Landmarks to be Lit in Pink to Celebrate Signing of the Reproductive Health Act|date=January 22, 2019|website=Governor Andrew M. Cuomo|accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FN12419\">[https://www.foxnews.com/politics/new-york-celebrates-legalizing-abortion-until-birth-as-catholic-bishops-question-cuomos-faith New York 'celebrates' legalizing abortion until birth as Catholic bishops question Cuomo's faith] (Fox News)</ref> Cuomo's signing and the lighting of the World Trade Center building sparked intense criticism from conservatives.<ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/politics/cuomo-defies-catholic-church-with-new-york-abortion-law-im-not-here-to-legislate-religion Cuomo brushes off criticism of New York abortion law: 'I'm not here to legislate religion'] (Fox News)</ref>\n\nCalls for Cuomo to be [[excommunicated]] from the [[Catholic Church]] followed his signing the expanded abortion rights into law. Cuomo responded, \"The Catholic Church does not believe in a woman's right to choose. Yes, I understand their religious view, I'm not here to legislate religion.\" The [[cardinal Timothy Dolan]] also criticized Cuomo over the Reproductive Health Act.<ref>Joseph Spector | ''Democrat & Chronicle'', Excommunicating Cuomo? [https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/politics/albany/2019/01/28/excommunicating-cuomo-some-catholic-leaders-angered-over-new-abortion-law-new-york/2703530002/ Some Catholic leaders angered over new abortion law in New York], January 29, 2019</ref>\n\n=== Appointee donations controversy ===\nOn his first day in office, Cuomo renewed an executive order signed by Eliot Spitzer which prohibited Governors of New York from receiving donations from gubernatorial appointees.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/24/nyregion/cuomo-fund-raising-ethics-appointees.html|title=In Spite of Executive Order, Cuomo Takes Campaign Money From State Appointees|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=2018-02-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-24|last2=Rosenthal|first2=Brian M.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Armendariz|first3=Agustin}}</ref> A February 2018 investigation by ''The New York Times'', however, revealed that the Cuomo administration had quietly reinterpreted the order, and that Cuomo had collected $890,000 from 24 of his appointees, as well as $1.3 million from the spouses, children and businesses of appointees.<ref name=\":4\" /> Some donations were made to Cuomo just days after the donor was appointed.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn March 2018, ''The New York Times'' reported that Cuomo had rewritten the disclaimer language on his campaign website for the executive order barring donations from appointees.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/nyregion/cuomo-appointee-donations-campaign-finance.html|title=Cuomo, in Writing, Reinterprets Fund-Raising Ban on Appointees|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=2018-03-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-30|last2=Rosenthal|first2=Brian M.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The website added two caveats whereby some gubernatorial appointees are allowed to donate to the governor, which ''The Times'' said could potentially lead to more donations from appointees to the governor.<ref name=\":5\" /> The Cuomo campaign returned $2,500 donation from one appointee who was in violation of the new disclaimer, but still retains the approximately $890,000 raised from other appointees.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Remarks about right-wing conservatives ===\nIn a January 17, 2014, interview with Susan Arbetter on [[WCNY-FM|WCNY]]'s ''The Capital Pressroom'', Cuomo stated:\n\n{{quote|[New York Republicans] are searching to define their soul, that's what's going on. Is the Republican party in this state a moderate party or is it an extreme conservative party? ... The Republican Party candidates are running against the SAFE Act \u2014 it was voted for by moderate Republicans who run the Senate! Their problem is not me and the Democrats; their problem is themselves. Who are they? Are they these extreme conservatives who are right-to-life, pro-assault-weapon, anti-gay? Is that who they are? Because if that's who they are and they're the extreme conservatives, they have no place in the state of New York, because that's not who New Yorkers are. If they're moderate Republicans like in the Senate right now, who control the Senate \u2014 moderate Republicans have a place in their state. George Pataki was governor of this state as a moderate Republican, but not what you're hearing from them on the far right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.timesunion.com/capitol/archives/203801/cuomo-extreme-conservatives-have-no-place-in-the-state-of-new-york/|title=Cuomo: 'Extreme conservatives ... have no place in the state of New York'|work=Capitol Confidential}}</ref>}}\n\nThis remark received a major reaction in the conservative media. Radio host [[Glenn Beck]] wrote a letter to the governor regarding the remarks from the interview.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theblaze.com/contributions/gov-cuomo-are-we-welcome-in-new-york/|title=Glenn Beck's Open Letter to Gov. Cuomo: Are We Welcome in New York?|first=Glenn|last=Beck|work=The Blaze}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=August 2019}} [[Fox News]] contributor and radio/TV show host [[Sean Hannity]] mentioned moving with all of his assets out of the state if the governor did not apologize for his remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/on-the-record/2014/01/22/sean-hannity-really-leaving-new-york-after-gov-cuomos-anti-conservative-comments|title=Is Sean Hannity really leaving New York after Gov. Cuomo's anti-conservative comments? \u2013 OTR Interviews \u2013 On the Record|publisher=Fox News Channel|access-date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701084404/http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/on-the-record/2014/01/22/sean-hannity-really-leaving-new-york-after-gov-cuomos-anti-conservative-comments|archive-date=July 1, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cardinal [[Timothy M. Dolan]], the [[Archbishop of New York]], said during a radio broadcast that the governor's remarks were \"most unfortunate at best. Are there pro-lifers who are extremist? Yes, there are. But I think they are a distinct minority.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/nyregion/cuomo-comment-elicits-retort-from-republicans.html|title=Comment by Cuomo outrages Republicans|date=January 22, 2014|author=McKinley, J.|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York State Democratic Committee]], which is headed by Cuomo, supported his remarks and reiterated them in a May 2014 statement responding to a speech by [[Rob Astorino]], who was running against him in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 gubernatorial election]]: \"Tea Party Republicans have done enough damage in Washington, today's speech made it abundantly clear that we don't need them here in New York.\"<ref>Reisman, Nick (May 15, 2014). [http://www.nystateofpolitics.com/2014/05/democrats-blast-astorino-speech/ Democrats blast Astorino speech]. ''Time Warner Cable News''. Retrieved May 15, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Andrew Cuomo}}\n\n== Personal life ==\nCuomo married [[Kerry Kennedy]], the seventh child of [[Robert F. Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Skakel Kennedy]], on June 9, 1990. They have three daughters: twins, Cara Ethel Kennedy-Cuomo and Mariah Matilda Kennedy-Cuomo (born 1995), and Michaela Andrea Kennedy-Cuomo (born 1997).<ref name=\"NYPost010311\" /><ref name=\"people\" /> They separated in 2003, and divorced in 2005. He began dating [[Food Network]] host [[Sandra Lee (chef)|Sandra Lee]] in 2005 and the couple moved in together in 2011. The two resided in [[Westchester County, New York]].<ref name=\"PolDaily010711\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Gibson |url=http://www.politicsdaily.com/2011/01/07/andrew-cuomo-takes-communion-and-revives-the-good-catholic-deb/ |title=Andrew Cuomo Takes Communion and Revives the 'Good Catholic' Debate |work=[[Politics Daily]] |date=January 7, 2011 |accessdate=April 15, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121023630/http://www.politicsdaily.com/2011/01/07/andrew-cuomo-takes-communion-and-revives-the-good-catholic-deb |archivedate=January 21, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYPost010311\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Fermino |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/cuomo_soul_mate_settles_into_her_nmWFGoP83fWvz0ReZlU62L |title=Cuomo's gal talks about life as the governor's girlfriend |work=[[New York Post]] |date=January 3, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"people\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20700565,00.html|title=Sandra Lee and Gov. Andrew Cuomo Have Family Dinners at Home|work=People|date=17 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYDailyNews010211\">{{cite news |first=Glenn |last=Blain |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-01-02/local/27086115_1_ethics-training-mario-cuomo-state-government |title=On second day in office, Cuomo attends church with daughters and Sandra Lee | location=New York |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date=January 2, 2011 |accessdate=February 22, 2012}}</ref> On September 25, 2019, the couple announced that they had ended their relationship.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-sandra-lee.html Governor Cuomo and Sandra Lee Have Split Up] 25 September 2019. The New York Times.</ref> As of the fall of 2019, Cuomo is living in the [[New York State Executive Mansion]] in Albany on full-time basis.\n\nOn July 4, 2015, Cuomo presided over the wedding ceremony of his long-time friend [[Billy Joel]] to his fourth wife, Alexis Roderick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Cuomo-presides-over-surprise-Billy-Joel-wedding-6367106.php|newspaper=Times Union|title=Cuomo presides over surprise Billy Joel wedding|date=5 July 2015|accessdate=22 March 2020  }}</ref>\n\nCuomo is a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=\"NYT31811\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/19/nyregion/19cuomo.html A Cuomo Who Is Catholic but Hardly Theological] 18 March 2011. New York Times.</ref> According to the ''New York Times'', Cuomo's positions in favor of abortion and same-sex marriage (and his cohabitation with Lee without marrying her)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120121023630/http://www.politicsdaily.com/2011/01/07/andrew-cuomo-takes-communion-and-revives-the-good-catholic-deb Andrew Cuomo Takes Communion and Revives the 'Good Catholic' Debate] (AOL, Huffington Post)</ref> contrary to church teachings have \"become a lightning rod in a decades-old culture war between conservative Catholics and those, like Mr. Cuomo, who disagree with the church's positions on various issues, including abortion and divorce.\"<ref name=\"NYT31811\"/>\n\n== Published works ==\n* Cuomo, Andrew. ''All Things Possible: Setbacks and Success in Politics and Life'', New York: Harper, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-06-230008-9}}.\n* Cuomo, Andrew. ''Crossroads: The Future of American Politics'', New York: Random House, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1400061457}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links| collapsible=yes | commonscat=yes | author=yes | b=no | voy=no | v=no | wikt=no}}\n* [http://www.governor.ny.gov/ Governor Andrew M. Cuomo] official New York government site\n* [http://andrewcuomo.com/ Andrew Cuomo for Governor]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Executive/Governor_Andrew_Cuomo}}\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Henry Cisneros]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]]|years=1997\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mel Martinez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Paterson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of New York]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betsy McCaughey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of New York|Liberal]] nominee for [[Governor of New York]]|years=[[New York gubernatorial election, 2002|2002]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=No ballot line}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Eliot Spitzer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[New York Attorney General|Attorney General of New York]]|years=[[New York attorney general election, 2006|2006]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Eric Schneiderman]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Governor of New Y