|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2001\u201302\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL2]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2002\u201303\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL2]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2003\u201304\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL2]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|[[File:Arrow-up.gif|Promoted to the Tehran Province league]]\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2004\u201305\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|15\n|5\n|4\n|6\n|27\n|25\n|21\n|7th\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2005\u201306\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2006\u201307\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2007\u201308\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2008\u201309\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=left|\n|[[File:Arrow-up.gif|Promoted to the Iran Football's 3rd Division]]\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2009\u201310\n|[[2009\u201310 Iran Football's 3rd Division|Div 3]]\n|22\n|12\n|5\n|5\n|43\n|26\n|41\n|2nd\n|align=left|\n|\n|align=left|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2010\u201311\n|[[2010\u201311 Iran Football's 3rd Division|Div 3]]\n|22\n|11\n|7\n|4\n|34\n|20\n|10\n|4th\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2011\u201312\n|[[2011\u201312 Iran Football's 3rd Division|Div 3]]\n|22\n|1\n|5\n|16\n|18\n|62\n|8\n|12th\n|\n|[[File:Arrow-down.gif|Relegated to the Tehran Province league Div 2]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2012\u201313\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2013\u201314\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2014\u201315\n|[[Tehran Province league|TFL]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2015-16\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2016-17\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!2017-18\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Key===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-4}}\n* P = Played\n* W = Games won\n* D = Games drawn\n* L = Games lost\n* F = Goals for\n* A = Goals against\n* Pts = Points\n* Pos = Final position\n{{col-4}}\n* TJC = [[Takht Jamshid Cup]]\n* TFL = [[Tehran Province league|Tehran Football League]]\n* TFL2 = [[Tehran Province league|Tehran Football League's 2nd Div.]]\n* Div 3 = [[Iran Football's 3rd Division|3rd Division]]\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|bgcolor=gold|<small>Champions</small>\n|bgcolor=silver|<small>Runners-up</small>\n|}\n\n==Founder and manager==\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} Dr. [[Abbas Ekrami]] (1942\u20131970)\n\n==Managers==\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Shapoor Sarhadi]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Amirhoshang Nikkhah Baharami]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Jafar Kashani]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Amirhoshang Nikkhah Bahrami]]\n\n==World Cup players<ref>http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1978/squad_irn78.html</ref>==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Nasrollah Abdollahi]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Nasser Hejazi]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Ebrahim Ghasempour]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Hamid-Majid Tajmuri]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Majid Bishkar]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hazfi Cup]]\n* [[2011\u201312 Iran Football's 3rd Division|Iran Football's 3rd Division 2011\u201312]]\n\n===Official===\n* {{in lang|fa}} [http://www.shahinfc.net/ Official club website]\n\n{{Football in Iran}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Iran]]\n[[Category:Defunct football clubs in Iran]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Sport in Tehran]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Iran]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahin_Tehran_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Durham Academy", "text_new": "{{advert|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Durham Academy\n| logo = Durham academy logo.png\n| image = Durham Academy Lower School.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 3601 Academy Road\n| city = [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| zipcode = 27705\n| country = United States\n| coordinates = {{Coord|35.97692|-78.97006|type:city_region:US|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Private School|Private]]\n| founded = 1933\n| headmaster = Michael Ulku-Steiner <br>\n| gender = multi\n| staff = 197\n| grades = [[Pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] to [[twelfth grade|Grade 12]]\n| athletics_conference = TISAC\n| mascot = [[Cavalier]]\n| accreditation = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]]\n| affiliations = [[National Association of Independent Schools|NAIS]], NCAIS\n| website = {{URL|da.org}}\n| tuition = $28,170 (grades 9-12)<br />$27,210 (grades 5-8)<br />$22,700 (grades 1\u20134)<br />$14,530 (Pre-K and Kindergarten)\n| students = 1,229\n| campus = [[Suburb]]an, {{convert|40|acre|ha}}\n| colors = Green and White<br />{{color box|#008000}} {{color box|white}}\n| pushpin_map = North Carolina#USA\n}}\n\n'''Durham Academy''' is an [[Independent school|independent]], [[coeducational]], college preparatory day school in [[Durham, North Carolina]], whose 1,229 students range from pre-kindergarten to grade 12. \n\nThe school has four divisions, each with its own director: Preschool (Pre-kindergarten/Kindergarten), Lower School (grades 1-4), Middle School (grades 5-8) and Upper School (grades 9-12). These are arrayed on three campuses that comprise four acres. \n\nThirty-eight percent of Durham Academy's students are people of color, as are 17 percent of teachers.\n\nIn 2019-20, Durham Academy awarded more than $2,200,000 in financial aid (not including tuition remission and need-based financial aid for faculty and staff); the average award was $14,682.\n\nDurham Academy's official mission is \"to provide each student an education that will enable him or her to live a moral, happy and productive life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.da.org/page.cfm?p=505|title=Durham Academy Mission and History|website=www.da.org|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDurham Academy was founded in 1933, as the Calvert Method School, by George Watts Hill and his wife Ann McCollough Hill. The couple established the school as a private, independent school to educate their children. The school's teaching philosophy (and its name) were based on the Calvert School in Baltimore, Maryland, which Ann McCollough Hill attended as a child. The Calvert Method School's first home was in Durham's [[Forest Hills Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)|Forest Hills neighborhood]], with the neighborhood's clubhouse serving as a classroom for seven students and one teacher.\n\nIn 1937, the Calvert Method School moved to [[John Sprunt Hill]]'s former home at 815 S. Duke Street.\n\nIn 1959, the school ended its affiliation with Baltimore's Calvert School and changed its name to Durham Academy. Durham Academy also became a member of the National Council of Independent Schools and added an eighth grade.\n\nIn May 1965, Durham Academy broke ground on a new campus on Highway 751 (later named Academy Road). Students and teachers moved into the new facility in March 1966.\n\nDurham Academy added to the Academy Road campus during the early 1970s. Plans for a starting high school were also explored.\n\nIn 1971, Durham Academy purchased and broke ground on 42 acres of land on Ridge Road to launch the Upper School. The Upper School opened in September 1973, and Durham Academy's first senior class graduated in June 1975. George Watts Hill and Frank Hawkins Kenan were both instrumental in the creation of Durham Academy's Upper School. Kenan, whose children had attended Calvert Method School and later Durham Academy, made an anonymous gift of $1 million to build the Upper School campus. George Watts Hill established an endowment for Durham Academy, to which Kenan later contributed nearly $3 million.\n\nIn 1977, George Watts Hill, Fred Brooks and Bill Friday founded the Learning Development Center (now known as The Hill Center), for children with learning differences. The LDC, located on Durham Academy's Ridge Road campus, had a close relationship with Durham Academy, but had its own faculty and a separate facility for its 13 students and four teachers. The Hill Center currently operates as an affiliate of Durham Academy in its facility on Pickett Rd. The center's focus is on intensive remediation and tutoring for students with learning differences and training teachers to help students with learning differences.\n\nBy 1978 Durham Academy had grown to 795 students in grades K-12. From the late 1970s to early 1980s the school developed an honor code, a Cum Laude Society, a faculty summer grants program and established an excellence in teaching award named after then-headmaster F. Robertson Hershey.\n\nIn 1983, Durham Academy celebrated its 50th anniversary with ceremonies led by founder George Watts Hill.\n\nIn 1986, the school added to the Academy Road campus with a new library/arts/science building. That same year, Durham Academy began hosting the Durham County Special Olympics, which includes an estimated 400 athletes from all Durham County Public Schools. Upper School students and faculty plan the annual event. The entire Upper School closes on the day of the games so that students and faculty can all volunteer and host the athletes.\n\nThe late 1980s and early 1990s saw major Middle School and Upper School expansions, the systematic development of Upper School experiential education programming and growth in the number of Durham Academy athletic teams to twice their size.\n\nIn the mid-1990s, Durham Academy parent Gary Hock donated a 6,000-square foot building to house computer classrooms and a computer library.\n\nIn August 2002, Durham Academy's Preschool and Lower School moved to 17 acres on the Ridge Road campus. The building opened has been recognized by the [[Chicago Athenaeum]]: Museum of Architecture and Design for its unique style.<ref>{{cite web |title=American Architecture Awards |publisher=Chicago Anthenaeum Museum of Architecture and Design |url=http://www.chi-athenaeum.org/archawards/2004/lowerschooldurham.html |accessdate=2006-12-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008221108/http://www.chi-athenaeum.org/archawards/2004/lowerschooldurham.html |archivedate=2006-10-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the school was ranked first in the Southeast by the New York Times and 30th in the nation by Forbes.\n\nDuring the 2008-2009 school year, Durham Academy celebrated its 75th anniversary.\n\nThe Upper School Learning Commons opened in February 2012. The 7,000-square-foot building includes a library, college counseling, a student store, a faculty work room, and a computer lab with 20 iMac stations. The building also houses classroom and office space.<ref>{{cite news|title=A new 'heart and soul' at Durham Academy |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/view/full_story/17519810/article-A-new-%E2%80%98heart-and-soul%E2%80%99-at-Durham-Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=Durham Herald-Sun }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Upper School Kirby Gym opened in January 2013. The extensive facility renovation and expansion resulted in seating for 900 spectators, a fitness center, locker rooms and trainer facility.\n\nDurham Academy received widespread press<ref>{{cite web|last=Alsup |first=Dave |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/12/us/school-closure-rap/ |title=Collaborate and listen: School closure announced with 'Ice Ice Baby' |publisher=CNN.com |date=2014-02-13 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posttv/national/durham-academy-weather-announcement-video/2014/02/13/0a1e470c-94c4-11e3-9e13-770265cf4962_video.html |title=Durham Academy weather announcement video |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2014-02-13 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>[http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/02/13/4690350/durham-academys-hilarious-closings.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221211915/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/02/13/4690350/durham-academys-hilarious-closings.html|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref> on February 12, 2014, after school administrators used rap music in a video<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HhtqjdUi0nw |title=Durham Academy Weather Announcement |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> announcing that the school would be closed due to snow.\n\nIn 2015, Durham Academy's auditioned [[a cappella]] group, XIV Hours, released a video entitled \"Lost in the Game\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/138636169 |title=Lost In The Game: A Musical Story of Relationships, Sex and Gender Politics on Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo.com |date=2015-09-08 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> that discussed the sexual nature of many popular song lyrics. The video quickly became popular and was covered in several major news sites, including MTV and the Huffington Post. The music video was also nominated for Best High School Video in the 2016 CASA A Capella Video awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.casa.org/ava2017n|title=2017 A Cappella Video Award Nominees {{!}} A Cappella Music - The Contemporary A Cappella Society|website=www.casa.org|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>[[File:Durham Academy Upper School.jpg|thumb|The Upper School]]\n<br />\n\n==Academics==\nDurham Academy's academic standards are highly regarded. The school offers a rigorous and challenging college preparatory curriculum, including 29 AP courses for 2016-2017. The Class of 2016 matriculated to 49 colleges and universities. Students' Middle 50% SAT scores ranged from 600-720 in critical reading, 610-730 in math and 590-730 in writing, for a combined best of 1810-2150 on a 2400 scale.\n\nRecent graduates have been awarded Morehead Scholarships to UNC-Chapel Hill, Angier B. Duke and B.N. Duke Scholarships to Duke University and Park Scholarships to N.C. State University, as well as merit scholarships to Santa Clara, University of Southern California, Rochester Institute of Technology, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Davidson, Dickinson, Mount Holyoke, Furman, Elon, Rhodes, and Guilford. Graduates of the last five years have attended all Ivy League schools, numerous outstanding private, top liberal arts, and public universities.  \n\nStudents at Durham Academy have won national titles in chess <ref>{{cite web|title=Chess Champ |publisher=The Herald-Sun |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/pages/full_story/push?article-CHESS+CHAMP%20&id=11129106&instance=main_article |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711163453/http://www.heraldsun.com/pages/full_story/push?article-CHESS+CHAMP%20&id=11129106&instance=main_article |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-11 |accessdate=2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= National Girls Chess Tournament Results | publisher=The United States Chess Federation | url=http://main.uschess.org/assets/msa_joomla/XtblMain.php?201004181511.2-12856308 | accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref>  and debate,<ref>{{cite web | title =National Tournament Results | publisher =National Forensic League | url =http://www.nflonline.org/uploads/NationalTournament/09NFLResults.pdf | accessdate =2010-03-24 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090711112853/http://www.nflonline.org/uploads/NationalTournament/09NFLResults.pdf | archivedate =2009-07-11 }}</ref> and a member of the Class of 2007 was awarded second place in the Intel Science Talent Search.<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham senior bags national honor |publisher=News & Observer |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2007/03/14/94714/durham-senior-bags-national-honor.html?storylink=misearch |accessdate=2010-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714175259/http://www.newsobserver.com/2007/03/14/94714/durham-senior-bags-national-honor.html?storylink=misearch |archivedate=2011-07-14 }}</ref> Over the past four years, Durham Academy has had 49 National Merit Scholarship finalists.  \n\nSixty-four percent of faculty members hold advanced degrees, and they average 19 years of teaching experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admissions: Why DA? |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=4435 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204050120/http://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=4435 |archivedate=4 December 2012 }}</ref> Lower School science teacher Lyn Streck was named the 2008 NC Conservation Education Teacher of the Year for involving students, faculty and parents in a variety of environmental efforts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Durham Academy teacher wins state award |url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2009/03/21/193712/durham-academy-teacher-wins-state.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203214843/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2009/03/21/193712/durham-academy-teacher-wins-state.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=The Durham News |date=March 21, 2009 }}</ref> Meanwhile, Upper School history teacher Mike Spatola was recognized by the [[Stanford University|Stanford]] Teacher Tribute Initiative in 2011<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford honors Spatola with teaching award |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=204&id=735587&rc=1 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  and received a 2012 Outstanding Educator Award from the [[University of Chicago]]<ref>{{cite web|title=US teacher Mike Spatola earns University of Chicago honor |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=204&nid=803652 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nDurham Academy's athletic offerings include [[field hockey]], [[volleyball]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[tennis]], [[soccer]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[basketball]], [[lacrosse]], [[softball]], [[track and field]], [[baseball]] and [[golf]]. Durham Academy had the first high school boys lacrosse program in Durham County.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newton |first=David |title=Burgeoning lacrosse makes a play for Durham adolescents |url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2007/03/17/43329/burgeoning-lacrosse-makes-a-play.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203230407/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2007/03/17/43329/burgeoning-lacrosse-makes-a-play.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=The Durham News |date=March 17, 2007 }}</ref>  Seventy-five percent of the students in grades seven through twelve participate in athletics, with 44 athletic teams in 20 different sports.\n\nSince 2010, Durham Academy has won 2 NCISAA state championships and had 10 NCISAA championship runner-up finishes. In 2015-2016, the school had 51 TISAC All-Conference athletes, 14 NCISAA All-State athletes and 4 All-American athletes.\n\nThe girls cross country team won the 2018 NCISAA state championship. The boys cross country team won the TISAC conference championship title in 2018 and placed second at the NCISAA state championship. The varsity girls field hockey team won the 2012 North Carolina Independent Schools Athletic Association championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/10/28/2446562/durham-academy-wins-field-hockey.html|title=Durham Academy wins field hockey; Broughton's Kane takes tennis|last=Malenick|first=Dave|newspaper=News & Observer|accessdate=1 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815175012/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/10/28/2446562/durham-academy-wins-field-hockey.html|archivedate=15 August 2014}}</ref> The cross country and track programs at Durham Academy are particularly notable, with 39 team state championships and 196 individual titles during the tenure of former head coach Dennis Cullen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/community/durham-news/dn-sports/article22186992.html|title=Cullen turned individual runners into a team|website=News and Observer|last1=Kim|first1=Veronica|accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\nSeveral Durham Academy athletes have gone on to [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] programs, including [[Duke University]], [[University of Vermont]], [[United States Naval Academy|U.S. Naval Academy]], [[Wake Forest University]], [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Durham native perseveres... |publisher=News & Observer |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/16/391648/grief-joy-find-player.html |accessdate=2010-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323060100/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/16/391648/grief-joy-find-player.html |archivedate=2010-03-23 }}</ref> Among those athletes are Mollie Pathman, the 2009-2010 Gatorade National Girls Soccer Player,<ref>{{cite news|title=Durham Academy soccer players wins national honor |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/05/26/501394/patham-named-national-player-of.html |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=News & Observer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815175023/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/05/26/501394/patham-named-national-player-of.html |archivedate=15 August 2014 }}</ref> who played on the U.S. women's Under-20 national team at the 2012 World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|title=Pathman, Cobb lead U.S. women's under-20 roster |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/view/full_story/19670038/article-Pathman--Cobb-lead-U-S--women%E2%80%99s-under-20-roster |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=News & Observer }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Evan Fjeld, a McDonald's All-American nominee who graduated from the University of Vermont and has played professionally in the [[NBA Development League|NBA D-League]] as well as in Malta and Switzerland,<ref>{{cite web|title=Evan Fjeld basketball profile|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/player.asp?Cntry=SUI&PlayerID=163109|publisher=EuroBasket|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref> and Lauren Blazing, Duke's field hockey goalkeeper, who was one of three nominees for 2016 NCAA Woman of the Year,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211161350|title=Blazing 1 of 30 Honorees for NCAA Woman of the Year|newspaper=goduke.com|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> played with the USWNT in the 2016 Rio Olympics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teamusa.org/USA-Field-Hockey/Features/2016/July/06/Chasing-The-Dream-with-USWNT-Athlete-Lauren-Blazing|title=Chasing The Dream with USWNT Athlete Lauren Blazing|newspaper=Team USA|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> was a three-time All-American, a two-time Capital One first team Academic All-American athlete and won ACC Field Hockey Scholar-Athlete of the Year twice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205158531&|title=Lauren Blazing Bio|newspaper=goduke.com|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nDurham Academy's arts classes include chorus, band, photography, filmmaking, ceramics, mixed media arts, acting studio, screenwriting, playwriting, and various levels of dance.\n\nDurham Academy arts alumni include Alvin Ailey dancer and choreographer Hope Boykin,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/hope-boykin|title=Hope Boykin {{!}} Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|date=2010-02-09|newspaper=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> \"The Affair\" co-creator and showrunner [[Sarah Treem]], actor Ward Horton<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/article110616382.html|title=Durham Academy grad gets long-awaited break on CBS' 'Pure Genius'|newspaper=newsobserver|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> and NBC's \"The Voice\" Season 8 finalist [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|Lowell Oakley]].\n\n\"In the Pocket\", an audition-based musical group, has performed at venues around the city and the country. There are also several extracurricular [[a cappella]] singing groups.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.casa.org/content/interview-michael-meyer-durham-academys-xiv-hours|title = An Interview With Michael Meyer Of Durham Academy's XIV Hours|date = |accessdate =2015-11-25 |website = |publisher =Casa.org |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nXIV Hours has been included four times on Best of High School A Capella annual compilations, with their most recent inclusion on the 2017 compilation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://varsityvocals.com/boca-bohsa-2017-track-lists/|title=BOCA & BOHSA 2017 Track Lists|date=2016-12-01|newspaper=Varsity Vocals|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Speech and debate==\nDurham Academy's debate team has won various national and regional competitions, including the [[National Speech and Debate Association|NFL]] National Championship, Harvard, Glenbrooks, Wake Forest, George Mason, [[Florida Blue Key]], Laird Lewis, and the Sunvitational. In addition, the team has won multiple state and district championships. The team is led by director Crawford Leavoy and division directors Jeff Welty, Molly Harris, Connor Leech, and Jordan Curry.<ref>dadebate.com</ref>\n\nOver the past 10 years six teams have finished in the top 10 at the national championship tournament and four teams have placed in the top three. Almost 15% of the student body participates.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of high schools in North Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.da.org}}\n*[http://www.dadebate.org official Speech and Debate website]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Education in Durham County, North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Education in Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Schools in Durham County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Durham Academy\n| logo = Durham academy logo.png\n| image = Durham Academy Lower School.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 3601 Academy Road\n| city = [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| zipcode = 27705\n| country = United States\n| coordinates = {{Coord|35.97692|-78.97006|type:city_region:US|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[Private School|Private]]\n| founded = 1933\n| headmaster = Michael Ulku-Steiner <br>\n| gender = multi\n| staff = 197\n| grades = [[Pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] to [[twelfth grade|Grade 12]]\n| athletics_conference = TISAC\n| mascot = [[Cavalier]]\n| accreditation = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]]\n| affiliations = [[National Association of Independent Schools|NAIS]], NCAIS\n| website = {{URL|da.org}}\n| tuition = $28,170 (grades 9-12)<br />$27,210 (grades 5-8)<br />$22,700 (grades 1\u20134)<br />$14,530 (Pre-K and Kindergarten)\n| students = 1,229\n| campus = [[Suburb]]an, {{convert|40|acre|ha}}\n| colors = Green and White<br />{{color box|#008000}} {{color box|white}}\n| pushpin_map = North Carolina#USA\n}}\n\n'''Durham Academy''' is an [[Independent school|independent]], [[coeducational]], college preparatory day school in [[Durham, North Carolina]], whose 1,229 students range from pre-kindergarten to grade 12. \n\nThe school has four divisions, each with its own director: Preschool (Pre-kindergarten/Kindergarten), Lower School (grades 1-4), Middle School (grades 5-8) and Upper School (grades 9-12). These are arrayed on three campuses that comprise four acres. \n\nThirty-eight percent of Durham Academy's students are people of color, as are 17 percent of teachers.\n\nIn 2019-20, Durham Academy awarded more than $2,200,000 in financial aid (not including tuition remission and need-based financial aid for faculty and staff); the average award was $14,682.\n\nDurham Academy's official mission is \"to provide each student an education that will enable him or her to live a moral, happy and productive life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.da.org/page.cfm?p=505|title=Durham Academy Mission and History|website=www.da.org|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDurham Academy was founded in 1933, as the Calvert Method School, by George Watts Hill and his wife Ann McCollough Hill. The couple established the school as a private, independent school to educate their children. The school's teaching philosophy (and its name) were based on the Calvert School in Baltimore, Maryland, which Ann McCollough Hill attended as a child. The Calvert Method School's first home was in Durham's [[Forest Hills Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)|Forest Hills neighborhood]], with the neighborhood's clubhouse serving as a classroom for seven students and one teacher.\n\nIn 1937, the Calvert Method School moved to [[John Sprunt Hill]]'s former home at 815 S. Duke Street.\n\nIn 1959, the school ended its affiliation with Baltimore's Calvert School and changed its name to Durham Academy. Durham Academy also became a member of the National Council of Independent Schools and added an eighth grade.\n\nIn May 1965, Durham Academy broke ground on a new campus on Highway 751 (later named Academy Road). Students and teachers moved into the new facility in March 1966.\n\nDurham Academy added to the Academy Road campus during the early 1970s. Plans for a starting high school were also explored.\n\nIn 1971, Durham Academy purchased and broke ground on 42 acres of land on Ridge Road to launch the Upper School. The Upper School opened in September 1973, and Durham Academy's first senior class graduated in June 1975. George Watts Hill and Frank Hawkins Kenan were both instrumental in the creation of Durham Academy's Upper School. Kenan, whose children had attended Calvert Method School and later Durham Academy, made an anonymous gift of $1 million to build the Upper School campus. George Watts Hill established an endowment for Durham Academy, to which Kenan later contributed nearly $3 million.\n\nIn 1977, George Watts Hill, Fred Brooks and Bill Friday founded the Learning Development Center (now known as The Hill Center), for children with learning differences. The LDC, located on Durham Academy's Ridge Road campus, had a close relationship with Durham Academy, but had its own faculty and a separate facility for its 13 students and four teachers. The Hill Center currently operates as an affiliate of Durham Academy in its facility on Pickett Rd. The center's focus is on intensive remediation and tutoring for students with learning differences and training teachers to help students with learning differences.\n\nBy 1978 Durham Academy had grown to 795 students in grades K-12. From the late 1970s to early 1980s the school developed an honor code, a Cum Laude Society, a faculty summer grants program and established an excellence in teaching award named after then-headmaster F. Robertson Hershey.\n\nIn 1983, Durham Academy celebrated its 50th anniversary with ceremonies led by founder George Watts Hill.\n\nIn 1986, the school added to the Academy Road campus with a new library/arts/science building. That same year, Durham Academy began hosting the Durham County Special Olympics, which includes an estimated 400 athletes from all Durham County Public Schools. Upper School students and faculty plan the annual event. The entire Upper School closes on the day of the games so that students and faculty can all volunteer and host the athletes.\n\nThe late 1980s and early 1990s saw major Middle School and Upper School expansions, the systematic development of Upper School experiential education programming and growth in the number of Durham Academy athletic teams to twice their size.\n\nIn the mid-1990s, Durham Academy parent Gary Hock donated a 6,000-square foot building to house computer classrooms and a computer library.\n\nIn August 2002, Durham Academy's Preschool and Lower School moved to 17 acres on the Ridge Road campus. The building opened has been recognized by the [[Chicago Athenaeum]]: Museum of Architecture and Design for its unique style.<ref>{{cite web |title=American Architecture Awards |publisher=Chicago Anthenaeum Museum of Architecture and Design |url=http://www.chi-athenaeum.org/archawards/2004/lowerschooldurham.html |accessdate=2006-12-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061008221108/http://www.chi-athenaeum.org/archawards/2004/lowerschooldurham.html |archivedate=2006-10-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the school was ranked first in the Southeast by the New York Times and 30th in the nation by Forbes.\n\nDuring the 2008-2009 school year, Durham Academy celebrated its 75th anniversary.\n\nThe Upper School Learning Commons opened in February 2012. The 7,000-square-foot building includes a library, college counseling, a student store, a faculty work room, and a computer lab with 20 iMac stations. The building also houses classroom and office space.<ref>{{cite news|title=A new 'heart and soul' at Durham Academy |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/view/full_story/17519810/article-A-new-%E2%80%98heart-and-soul%E2%80%99-at-Durham-Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=Durham Herald-Sun }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Upper School Kirby Gym opened in January 2013. The extensive facility renovation and expansion resulted in seating for 900 spectators, a fitness center, locker rooms and trainer facility.\n\nDurham Academy received widespread press<ref>{{cite web|last=Alsup |first=Dave |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/02/12/us/school-closure-rap/ |title=Collaborate and listen: School closure announced with 'Ice Ice Baby' |publisher=CNN.com |date=2014-02-13 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posttv/national/durham-academy-weather-announcement-video/2014/02/13/0a1e470c-94c4-11e3-9e13-770265cf4962_video.html |title=Durham Academy weather announcement video |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2014-02-13 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>[http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/02/13/4690350/durham-academys-hilarious-closings.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221211915/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/02/13/4690350/durham-academys-hilarious-closings.html|date=February 21, 2014}}</ref> on February 12, 2014, after school administrators used rap music in a video<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HhtqjdUi0nw |title=Durham Academy Weather Announcement |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> announcing that the school would be closed due to snow.\n\nIn 2015, Durham Academy's auditioned [[a cappella]] group, XIV Hours, released a video entitled \"Lost in the Game\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/138636169 |title=Lost In The Game: A Musical Story of Relationships, Sex and Gender Politics on Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo.com |date=2015-09-08 |accessdate=2015-11-26}}</ref> that discussed the sexual nature of many popular song lyrics. The video quickly became popular and was covered in several major news sites, including MTV and the Huffington Post. The music video was also nominated for Best High School Video in the 2016 CASA A Capella Video awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.casa.org/ava2017n|title=2017 A Cappella Video Award Nominees {{!}} A Cappella Music - The Contemporary A Cappella Society|website=www.casa.org|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>[[File:Durham Academy Upper School.jpg|thumb|The Upper School]]\n<br />\n\n==Academics==\nDurham Academy's academic standards are highly regarded. The school offers a rigorous and challenging college preparatory curriculum, including 29 AP courses for 2016-2017. The Class of 2016 matriculated to 49 colleges and universities. Students' Middle 50% SAT scores ranged from 600-720 in critical reading, 610-730 in math and 590-730 in writing, for a combined best of 1810-2150 on a 2400 scale.\n\nRecent graduates have been awarded Morehead Scholarships to UNC-Chapel Hill, Angier B. Duke and B.N. Duke Scholarships to Duke University and Park Scholarships to N.C. State University, as well as merit scholarships to Santa Clara, University of Southern California, Rochester Institute of Technology, Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Davidson, Dickinson, Mount Holyoke, Furman, Elon, Rhodes, and Guilford. Graduates of the last five years have attended all Ivy League schools, numerous outstanding private, top liberal arts, and public universities.  \n\nStudents at Durham Academy have won national titles in chess <ref>{{cite web|title=Chess Champ |publisher=The Herald-Sun |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/pages/full_story/push?article-CHESS+CHAMP%20&id=11129106&instance=main_article |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711163453/http://www.heraldsun.com/pages/full_story/push?article-CHESS+CHAMP%20&id=11129106&instance=main_article |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-11 |accessdate=2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= National Girls Chess Tournament Results | publisher=The United States Chess Federation | url=http://main.uschess.org/assets/msa_joomla/XtblMain.php?201004181511.2-12856308 | accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref>  and debate,<ref>{{cite web | title =National Tournament Results | publisher =National Forensic League | url =http://www.nflonline.org/uploads/NationalTournament/09NFLResults.pdf | accessdate =2010-03-24 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090711112853/http://www.nflonline.org/uploads/NationalTournament/09NFLResults.pdf | archivedate =2009-07-11 }}</ref> and a member of the Class of 2007 was awarded second place in the Intel Science Talent Search.<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham senior bags national honor |publisher=News & Observer |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2007/03/14/94714/durham-senior-bags-national-honor.html?storylink=misearch |accessdate=2010-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714175259/http://www.newsobserver.com/2007/03/14/94714/durham-senior-bags-national-honor.html?storylink=misearch |archivedate=2011-07-14 }}</ref> Over the past four years, Durham Academy has had 49 National Merit Scholarship finalists.  \n\nSixty-four percent of faculty members hold advanced degrees, and they average 19 years of teaching experience.<ref>{{cite web |title=Admissions: Why DA? |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=4435 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204050120/http://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=4435 |archivedate=4 December 2012 }}</ref> Lower School science teacher Lyn Streck was named the 2008 NC Conservation Education Teacher of the Year for involving students, faculty and parents in a variety of environmental efforts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Durham Academy teacher wins state award |url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2009/03/21/193712/durham-academy-teacher-wins-state.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203214843/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2009/03/21/193712/durham-academy-teacher-wins-state.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=The Durham News |date=March 21, 2009 }}</ref> Meanwhile, Upper School history teacher Mike Spatola was recognized by the [[Stanford University|Stanford]] Teacher Tribute Initiative in 2011<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford honors Spatola with teaching award |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=204&id=735587&rc=1 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  and received a 2012 Outstanding Educator Award from the [[University of Chicago]]<ref>{{cite web|title=US teacher Mike Spatola earns University of Chicago honor |url=https://www.da.org/podium/default.aspx?t=204&nid=803652 |publisher=Durham Academy |accessdate=1 November 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nDurham Academy's athletic offerings include [[field hockey]], [[volleyball]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[tennis]], [[soccer]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[basketball]], [[lacrosse]], [[softball]], [[track and field]], [[baseball]] and [[golf]]. Durham Academy had the first high school boys lacrosse program in Durham County.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newton |first=David |title=Burgeoning lacrosse makes a play for Durham adolescents |url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2007/03/17/43329/burgeoning-lacrosse-makes-a-play.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203230407/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2007/03/17/43329/burgeoning-lacrosse-makes-a-play.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 3, 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=The Durham News |date=March 17, 2007 }}</ref>  Seventy-five percent of the students in grades seven through twelve participate in athletics, with 44 athletic teams in 20 different sports.\n\nSince 2010, Durham Academy has won 2 NCISAA state championships and had 10 NCISAA championship runner-up finishes. In 2015-2016, the school had 51 TISAC All-Conference athletes, 14 NCISAA All-State athletes and 4 All-American athletes.\n\nThe girls cross country team won the 2018 NCISAA state championship. The boys cross country team won the TISAC conference championship title in 2018 and placed second at the NCISAA state championship. The varsity girls field hockey team won the 2012 North Carolina Independent Schools Athletic Association championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/10/28/2446562/durham-academy-wins-field-hockey.html|title=Durham Academy wins field hockey; Broughton's Kane takes tennis|last=Malenick|first=Dave|newspaper=News & Observer|accessdate=1 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815175012/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/10/28/2446562/durham-academy-wins-field-hockey.html|archivedate=15 August 2014}}</ref> The cross country and track programs at Durham Academy are particularly notable, with 39 team state championships and 196 individual titles during the tenure of former head coach Dennis Cullen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/community/durham-news/dn-sports/article22186992.html|title=Cullen turned individual runners into a team|website=News and Observer|last1=Kim|first1=Veronica|accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\nSeveral Durham Academy athletes have gone on to [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] programs, including [[Duke University]], [[University of Vermont]], [[United States Naval Academy|U.S. Naval Academy]], [[Wake Forest University]], [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Durham native perseveres... |publisher=News & Observer |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/16/391648/grief-joy-find-player.html |accessdate=2010-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323060100/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/03/16/391648/grief-joy-find-player.html |archivedate=2010-03-23 }}</ref> Among those athletes are Mollie Pathman, the 2009-2010 Gatorade National Girls Soccer Player,<ref>{{cite news|title=Durham Academy soccer players wins national honor |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/05/26/501394/patham-named-national-player-of.html |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=News & Observer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815175023/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/05/26/501394/patham-named-national-player-of.html |archivedate=15 August 2014 }}</ref> who played on the U.S. women's Under-20 national team at the 2012 World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|title=Pathman, Cobb lead U.S. women's under-20 roster |url=http://www.heraldsun.com/view/full_story/19670038/article-Pathman--Cobb-lead-U-S--women%E2%80%99s-under-20-roster |accessdate=1 November 2012 |newspaper=News & Observer }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Evan Fjeld, a McDonald's All-American nominee who graduated from the University of Vermont and has played professionally in the [[NBA Development League|NBA D-League]] as well as in Malta and Switzerland,<ref>{{cite web|title=Evan Fjeld basketball profile|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/player.asp?Cntry=SUI&PlayerID=163109|publisher=EuroBasket|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref> and Lauren Blazing, Duke's field hockey goalkeeper, who was one of three nominees for 2016 NCAA Woman of the Year,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4200&ATCLID=211161350|title=Blazing 1 of 30 Honorees for NCAA Woman of the Year|newspaper=goduke.com|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> played with the USWNT in the 2016 Rio Olympics,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teamusa.org/USA-Field-Hockey/Features/2016/July/06/Chasing-The-Dream-with-USWNT-Athlete-Lauren-Blazing|title=Chasing The Dream with USWNT Athlete Lauren Blazing|newspaper=Team USA|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> was a three-time All-American, a two-time Capital One first team Academic All-American athlete and won ACC Field Hockey Scholar-Athlete of the Year twice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goduke.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205158531&|title=Lauren Blazing Bio|newspaper=goduke.com|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Arts==\nDurham Academy's arts classes include chorus, band, photography, filmmaking, ceramics, mixed media arts, acting studio, screenwriting, playwriting, and various levels of dance.\n\nDurham Academy arts alumni include Alvin Ailey dancer and choreographer <nowiki>[[Hope Boykin]]</nowiki>,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.alvinailey.org/alvin-ailey-american-dance-theater/hope-boykin|title=Hope Boykin {{!}} Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|date=2010-02-09|newspaper=Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> \"The Affair\" co-creator and showrunner [[Sarah Treem]], actor Ward Horton<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/article110616382.html|title=Durham Academy grad gets long-awaited break on CBS' 'Pure Genius'|newspaper=newsobserver|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref> and NBC's \"The Voice\" Season 8 finalist [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|Lowell Oakley]].\n\n\"In the Pocket\", an audition-based musical group, has performed at venues around the city and the country. There are also several extracurricular [[a cappella]] singing groups.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.casa.org/content/interview-michael-meyer-durham-academys-xiv-hours|title = An Interview With Michael Meyer Of Durham Academy's XIV Hours|date = |accessdate =2015-11-25 |website = |publisher =Casa.org |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nXIV Hours has been included four times on Best of High School A Capella annual compilations, with their most recent inclusion on the 2017 compilation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://varsityvocals.com/boca-bohsa-2017-track-lists/|title=BOCA & BOHSA 2017 Track Lists|date=2016-12-01|newspaper=Varsity Vocals|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Speech and debate==\nDurham Academy's debate team has won various national and regional competitions, including the [[National Speech and Debate Association|NFL]] National Championship, Harvard, Glenbrooks, Wake Forest, George Mason, [[Florida Blue Key]], Laird Lewis, and the Sunvitational. In addition, the team has won multiple state and district championships. The team is led by director Crawford Leavoy and division directors Jeff Welty, Molly Harris, Connor Leech, and Jordan Curry.<ref>dadebate.com</ref>\n\nOver the past 10 years six teams have finished in the top 10 at the national championship tournament and four teams have placed in the top three. Almost 15% of the student body participates.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of high schools in North Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.da.org}}\n*[http://www.dadebate.org official Speech and Debate website]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Education in Durham County, North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Education in Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Schools in Durham County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Clonerg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Durham_Academy"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Singapore}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore\n| map1            = COVID-19 Cases in Singapore by Planning Areas.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of planning areas with confirmed (red) coronavirus cases (as of 9 April)}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Singapore]]\n| first_case      = 23 January 2020\n| arrival_date    = 23 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=23|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 683<ref name=\"worldometers\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |title=worldometers.info |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| deaths          = 10<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\">{{Cite web |url=https://coronaboard.com/ |title=COVID-19 Dashboard |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331135805/https://coronaboard.com/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 4,427<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg |title=Corona Tracker Overview |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143811/https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg/ |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>|Action taken: Circuit Breaker (7 Apr-4 May 2020)\nStatus: Enforcing (Expires: 4 May 2020; Tentative)\n| active          = \n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n| Deaths from other causes = \n| Death from other causes = 1\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore''' is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2).\n\nThe first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on 23 January.<ref name=\"Abdullah 2020\" /> To combat COVID-19, a multi-ministerial committee was formed on 22 January with Minister for National Development [[Lawrence Wong]] and Minister for Health [[Gan Kim Yong]] as the co-chairs and [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Minister for Finance [[Heng Swee Keat]] as advisors.<ref name=\"ST22Jan\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |title=Multi-Ministry Taskforce on Wuhan Coronavirus:  Terms of Reference (TORs) and Composition |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321054236/https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, Singapore announced a stringent set of preventive measures which were collectively called 'circuit breaker'. This will be applied from 7 April to 4 May 2020.\n[[Singapore]] contributed US$500,000 to support [[WHO]] efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore contributes US$500,000 to support WHO efforts against COVID-19 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNA |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325020159/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Singapore medical cases chart}}\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe top plot shows the total number of cases as a function of time (by date) since 23 January 2020, the date of the first reported case in Singapore. The bottom plot shows the number of new cases as reported each day.\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=orange, blue, red\n| legend=Legend\n| width = 900\n| height = 400\n| xAxisTitle = Date (day/month)\n| yAxisTitle = Total no. of cases (cumulative)\n| y1Title=Confirmed\n| y2Title=Recovered\n| y3Title=Deaths\n| xAxisAngle = -65\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n| x =  23/1, 24/1, 25/1, 26/1, 27/1, 28/1, 29/1, 30/1, 31/1, 1/2, 2/2, 3/2, 4/2, 5/2, 6/2, 7/2, 8/2, 9/2, 10/2, 11/2, 12/2, 13/2, 14/2, 15/2, 16/2, 17/2, 18/2, 19/2, 20/2, 21/2, 22/2, 23/2, 24/2, 25/2, 26/2, 27/2, 28/2, 29/2, 1/3, 2/3, 3/3, 4/3, 5/3, 6/3, 7/3, 8/3, 9/3, 10/3, 11/3, 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29/3, 30/3, 31/3, 1/4, 2/4, 3/4, 4/4, 5/4, 6/4, 7/4, 8/4, 9/4, 1